@node Registration "Registration"

Registrations for the TechnoBBS software are once again accepted.  The
responsibility for the distribution of registrations has changed hands,
registrations are now handled by Telemedia Software instead of the author
of this software.

To register this product, send 350 FIM (finnish marks) or $90 US.  As you
can see, if you pay in US Dollars, you have to pay a little more than if
you paid in finnish marks.  That's only because we have to change USD to
FIM before we can use them.  If possible use FIM.  All the major banks in
Europe and in the US exchange it.

The registration fee can be sent either in cash, or in any other form, as
long as we can cash it in directly (and for a low charge, if any) at a bank
located in Helsinki.

Along with the registration fee, you must include a letter stating that you
wish to register a product called TechnoBBS.  The letter should contain at
least the following information about yourself:

  - Full name (first, last)
  - Full address (street, city, postal/zip code, country, (state))
  - Voice/fax/BBS-number (and the name of the BBS, if any)
  - E-Mail address (if any)

Send your registration order to @{"Telemedia Software" link Telemedia}.

If you want to receive your keyfile faster, you can ask for it to be sent
to you PGP-encrypted via Internet E-Mail.  If you wish to use this method
you @{i}@{b}must@{ub} @{ui}provide the following information:

  - Your E-Mail address
  - Your PGP public key (in ASCII form)

Otherwise, the keyfile will be sent to your street address via regular
mail, on a disk, along with an archive containing the newest release of
TechnoBBS.

@endnode

@node Limitations "Limitations"

The unregistered version of TechnoBBS only accepts users with good timing.
An average of 50% of all the calls will fail.

@endnode

@node Updates "Updates"

There is no real difference between the actual registered/unregistered
TechnoBBS software.  Registered users receive a keyfile which disables the
restrictions (intended to encourage registration) of the freely
distributable TechnoBBS software.  This is useful, since registered users
can always get updates for no cost, (except what it costs them to download
the new distribution) as long as they can find the distribution somewhere
(which shouldn't be a problem, since freely distributable software has a
natural tendency to spread around the world).

You should be able to obtain the latest release of TechnoBBS from Aminet
(comm/bbs) shortly after its release.  You can probably also find new
releases on normal BBS's (especially ones running on TechnoBBS).

The authors BBS always has the newest TechnoBBS distribution available.  It
can be downloaded normally, or without logging on either by user freq (by
typing 'freq' at the mailer prompt) or by normal FidoNet filerequest.  (The
magic name 'TECHNOBBS' can be used for both).  The number of the BBS is
+358-0-635296 (V.FC, 24h).  (The number will probably change within a few
months, most likely before 1995)

You can also send 50 FIM (or $10 US) to @{"Telemedia Software" link Telemedia} to receive the
latest version by mail.  (You don't need to be registered)

@endnode

@node Introduction "Introduction"

@{b}@{i}TechnoBBS @{ub}@{ui}is a highly flexible bulletin board system for the Amiga line of
computers.

It is provided under the concept of @{"Shareware" link Shareware}.

@{"Registration" link Registration} isn't mandatory, but is practical, since there are some
@{"limitations" link Limitations} if you don't have a keyfile.

The registration fee for TechnoBBS is much higher than for most other
shareware products, but considerably lower than equivalent commercial
products (many of which are inferior to TechnoBBS by far and yet have a
much higher pricing (even considering that it may include a printed manual
etc.)).

The TechnoBBS system consists of 3 main executables:

        @{" TechCon     " link TechCon}
        @{" TechnoBBS   " link TechnoBBS}
        @{" TechMail    " link TechMail}

A few utilities are also included:

        @{" TechUserEd  " link TechUserEd}
        @{" TechQWK     " link TechQWK}
        @{" TechWWF     " link TechWWF}
        @{" TechIO      " link TechIO}
        @{" TechMenu    " link TechMenu}
        @{" TechFList   " link TechFList}
        @{" TrimArea    " link TrimArea}
        @{" MkFDat      " link MkFDat}
        @{" TFreq       " link TFreq}
        @{" PDoor       " link PDoor}

Note that these are listed as utilities, since they are not really required
by the BBS system for anything (since the whole system doesn't do anything
by default), it is entirely dependent on the sysop's configuration, which
ones are used.

@endnode

@node SystemReq "System Requirements"

  @{b}Hardware:@{ub}

TechnoBBS will run on any Amiga model with a 680x0 processor, Kickstart
2.04 or higher and at least 1MB (it'll probably just barely work, you'll
have to have a very simple configuration) of memory, though 1.5MB or more
is highly recommended.  A keyboard or equivalent may be required.  For
running a remote BBS, a hard drive is recommended and a modem or equivalent
device is necessary.

  @{b}Software:@{ub}

The standard libraries for the operating system release 2.04 or higher are
required, and for a remote node a mailer or equivalent should be used to
run TechnoBBS whenever a connection is made.  A device (usually
serial.device) for whatever type of modem or serial board you are using is
also necessary for remote operation.

@endnode

@node Features "Features"

One of TechnoBBSs strengths is that it's written for computers running
AmigaOS Release 2 or higher.  This allows it to take advantage of many
major improvements in the Amiga operating system that were introduced in
release 2, which makes it much more powerful than older software that is
restricted to using only functions available in older (now obsolete)
operating systems.

Here are some of the features of the TechnoBBS system:

  - Highly configurable menu-structure (can be created using ARexx or
    @{"TechMenu" link TechMenu} scripts)

  - You can make your BBS look like just about anything (and you should,
    since it isn't nice if all BBS's look the same), even supporting
    multiple languages for users

  - Relatively fast even on a 68000 (though an '020 or higher is useful)

  - Easy-to-read AmigaGuide manual (you're lookin' at it!)

  - GUIs have the "AmigaOS 2.0+ look" and are font-sensitive

  - Should be compatible with (and capable of using the screen modes of)
    any graphics boards

  - Pure executables to reduce memory consumption when multiple nodes are
    active simultaneously

  - Bi-directional file transfers are supported via the XPR 2.001 extension
    using protocols such as DModem

  - Remote-shell and stdio door support using TechIO

  - Excellent command line editing features (almost exactly like the
    Amiga's standard console, including command line history w/retype etc.)

  - Released as shareware, you can see how you like the software and try
    out all of the features (no important things, such as serial I/O, are
    disabled) before buying

  - Keyfile based registration policy enables an unlimited number of
    virtually free updates

  - Split screen chat with SysOp (and in the future, hopefully a similar
    chat between nodes), much more comfortable than a traditional chat

  - Should be compatible with any serial boards and devices

@endnode

@node Setup "Setting Up"

To set up the TechnoBBS system, first you must have all the files in the
right places.  Most of the files you might need are in their right places
when extracted from the archive to a directory which you would use for you
main bbs-directory.  The example configurations and scripts provided can
(and should) be customized before actual use, and the files in Menu/ must
be compiled (using @{"TechMenuComp" link TechMenuComp}) before usage.

Many people will want to configure their system from scratch, or need
options not provided in the example configurations.

        @{"  TechCon - Configuration    " link TechConCfg}
        @{"  TechnoBBS - Configuration  " link TechnoBBSCfg}
        @{"  TechMail - Configuration   " link TechMailCfg}

If you know ARexx, you might even want to write your own scripts for
operating your BBS.  It is recommended that you read through all the ARexx
commands (so you don't miss something important) and look at the example
scripts before attempting this.  You can also use @{"TechMenu" link TechMenu} for the menus,
but you need to use ARexx for the logon part.

        @{"  TechCon - ARexx    " link TechConARexx}
        @{"  TecnoBBS - ARexx   " link TechnoBBSARexx}

You must also configure any file and/or message areas that you want to
have.

        @{"  File Base Configuration    " link FileConfig}
        @{"  Message Base Configuration " link MessageConfig}

@endnode

@node FileConfig "File Base Configuration"

For now, there is no easy way to configure the file areas.  To create your
file areas you must create sub-directories in your configured file
directory for each area (except if you want all your files in your root
area).  These sub-directories can also have sub-directories etc.  Each
directory must have (or if a directory doesn't have one, it is assumed not
to be a file area) a file called 'filearea.dat' in them.  The lines of a
'filearea.dat' should contain the following:

 - The name of the file area
 - The minimum access for using the area
 - The minimum access for uploading to the area
 - The minimum access for downloading from the area
 - The mask required for access to the area
 - The mask required for uploading to the area
 - The mask required for downloading from the area

You can have any number of lines after this, they can be:

 - Empty lines are ignored

 - Lines that begin with a '+' indicate files in this area that are free to
   download.  The name of a free file is given after the '+'-character.
   Wildcards are valid.

 - Lines that begin with a '-' indicate files that are disallowed for
   upload.  The name is specified after the '-' and can contain wildcards.
   (If you don't want any uploads in the area, you could either have a high
   minimum access and/or mask for uploading or place a line containing
   "-#?" here)

 - Lines that begin with an '*' can be used for external utility
   configurations (such as TechFList).  There is one special use for these:
   '*->' indicates a redirection of the area.  There should be a path
   specified after the '*->'.  This path will be used for the actual files
   of this file area.  This way you can have file areas on several devices
   (the subdirectories of the redirected area are read from the redirected
   path, not from where the configuration is), eg.  hard drive partitions,
   floppy disks, or a CD-ROM.  You can also use:

   - *DATAFILE <filename>

     <filename> should be the name of a file (including its complete path)
     which is in the following format:

     Each line is one of:
     <blank lines are ignored>
     <filename>/<length>/<date>/<description>
     /<continuation to the description of the previous file>

     If a *DATAFILE is specified for an area, the actual directory of the
     area will not be read for each update.  The contents of the file area
     will be limited to the files contained in the *DATAFILE.  This feature
     can be used to speed up areas that can't be uploaded to (or that you
     intend to update manually), such as CD-ROM areas.  If you have a
     CD-ROM, @{"MkFDat" link MkFDat} can be useful for automatically generating areas with
     *DATAFILEs.

     Specifying a *DATAFILE for an area also changes the behavior of a
     redirection for that area.  The directory containing the filearea.dat
     is scanned for additional data and subdirectories instead of the
     redirected area.

     Note: *DESCFILE has been removed because it didn't work!  *DATAFILE
     replaces it and is much better.

You can also have a file called areasort.dat which contains the names of
subdirectories of the current directory, one on each line, (the directory
this areasort.dat is in) in the order they should appear on the BBS.  (This
is so the areas will have the same numbers even if you do something that
changes the order in which the areas are read from disk and so you can have
some control over the order of the areas)

@endnode

@node MessageConfig "Message Base Configuration"

For now, there is no easy way to configure the message areas.  For each of
the areas you have, you must have a file called MSGA<area number>.DAT in
the MsgDat/-subdirectory of your mail directory.  The lines of each of
these files should contain (these are not keyword-based):

 - The name of the message area
 - The type of area (0 for netmail, 1 for echo, 2 for local private, 3 for
   local public)
 - The low message number (set this to 0 if you are creating the area)
 - The high message number (set this to 0 if you are creating the area)
 - The current message file (set this to 0 if you are creating the area)
 - The minimum access for using this area
 - The minimum access for reading this area
 - The minimum access for writing to this area
 - The minimum access for reading private messages to others, killing
   messages and editing message bits in this area
 - The mask required for access to this area
 - The mask required for reading this area
 - The mask required for writing to this area
 - The mask required for reading private messages to others, killing
   messages and editing message bits in this area
 - The echo-area tag for this area (this line is ignored for other types of
   areas)
 - The hiwater mark for this area (set this to 0 if you are creating the
   area)
 - A flag indicating that messages shouldn't be imported to this area if
   non-zero.  This should be used if you are tossing echo-areas to other
   BBSs but don't want to have the messages of those echos on your BBS)

You can have any number of lines after this, they can be:

 - Empty lines are ignored

 - Lines that begin with an '*' are stored whether they have a valid
   keyword or not (these can be used for external utilities etc.).  The
   keywords used by the current system are:  '*ORIGIN' specifies an origin
   to use for the area.  If this is not specified, the default origin for
   the node will be used.  Origins only apply to echo-areas.  '*AKA'
   specifies an "AKA" (Also Known As) for an echo-area.  If you specify
   one, the 'AKA' address will be used instead of the default for messages
   processed in this area.  TechMail supports the following additional
   settings for echo-areas:

   - *INCSET <address> <character set>

     As @{"InCharSet" link TMInCharSet} in TechMail.Cfg, overrides for this area.

   - *OUTCSET <address> <character set>

     As @{"OutCharSet" link TMOutCharSet} in TechMail.Cfg, overrides for this area.

 - All other lines are node addresses (in the 4d address format:
   [[zone:]net/]node[.point]) indicating the nodes to export this area to.
   If they contain something else, they will probably turn into something
   strange and cause strange message bundles to be created.

You can also have a file called Sig.Dat in this same directory containing
SIG (a group of message areas) settings separated by a line containing a
"@" character.  The lines required for each SIG are:

 - SIG Name
 - Required access
 - Required mask
 - One or more lines listing message areas that are part of that SIG,
   separated by commas

(SIGs are useful for separating different types of areas, you might have
separate SIGs for message areas related to different computers or you could
have separate local and network SIGs etc.)

@endnode

@node TechCon "TechCon"

@{b}@{i}TechCon @{ub}@{ui}is the control process for the TechnoBBS system.  It is required
for running TechnoBBS nodes and provides a user interface for the SysOp to
control various features of any main TechnoBBS process, which is useful
when that process doesn't have a window open.

TechCon is responsible for the handling of messages and users (no other
programs should access them directly while TechCon is running).  TechCon
keeps a global clock (updated every 10 seconds) and filelist for the nodes
to save memory and processing time.

TechCon also provides a @{"CRON" link Cron} feature, ie.  it can
automatically activate predefined events at a set time.

To run TechCon from a CLI/Shell:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechCon [<Configuration file>]

If you don't specify a configuration file, TechCon will try to load
'BBS:Cfg/TechCon.Cfg'.

Once run, TechCon will open as a window on the workbench screen, a window
on a public screen which it also opens, or an AppIcon (by clicking this
TechCon will open a window), depending on it's configuration.

        @{"  TechCon - Configuration    " link TechConCfg}
        @{"  TechCon - Interface        " link TechConWin}
        @{"  TechCon - ARexx            " link TechConARexx}

TechCon is a commodity.  It supports most of the normal commodity commands
through the 'Commodities Exchange'-program.

The TechCon executable is pure, though that probably isn't of any use,
since it can't be run several times anyhow (except to bring up the existing
TechCon via the unique testing of the commodities system, in which having
TechCon resident would save some memory).

@endnode

@node TechConWin "TechCon - Interface"

        The TechCon window:

At the top of the TechCon window there is a rather large listview-gadget,
which displays the numbers of the possible TechnoBBS nodes.  If any nodes
are active, it also displays the status and user of that node.  The
listview can be used to select a node to which the functions of some of the
other gadgets apply to.  Keyboard shortcut:  keys 0-9 select nodes 0-9.

        Below the listview are three cycle-gadgets:

        @{b}SysOp Available/SysOp N/A@{ub}

Changes/shows whether the SysOp is available for the node selected from the
listview.  Enabled only for active nodes.  Keyboard shortcut:  'A'.

        @{b}Use Window/Background Only@{ub}

Opens/Closes the console window of the TechnoBBS node selected from the
listview.  Enabled only for active nodes.  Keyboard shortcut:  'N'.

        @{b}Serial Enabled/Serial Disabled@{ub}

Enables/Disables the serial access of the TechnoBBS node selected from the
listview.  Enabled only for active remote nodes.  Keyboard shortcut:  'S'.

        The 6 buttons:

        @{b}Launch@{ub}

Launches the TechnoBBS node selected in the listview.  Enabled only for
inactive nodes.  Keyboard shortcut:  'L'.

        @{b}LogOff@{ub}

Deactivates the TechnoBBS node selected in the listview.  Enabled only for
active nodes.  Keyboard shortcut:  'L'.  The keyboard shortcut can be
disabled using the @{"DisableLogoff" link TCDisableLogoff} configuration keyword.

NOTE:  Launch and LogOff have the same keyboard shortcut, but they can't be
enabled simultaneously.

        @{b}Chat@{ub}

Starts a chat with the user logged on to the TechnoBBS node selected in the
listview.  If the node doesn't have it's console window open, it will be
opened for the duration of the chat.  Enabled only for active nodes.
Keyboard shortcut:  'C'.

        @{b}Edit@{ub}

Launches the user editor using the configured commandline to edit the user
logged on to the node selected in the listview.  Enabled only for active
nodes with a user logged on.

        @{b}TechMail@{ub}

Starts TechMail using the configured commandline

        @{b}AppIcon@{ub}

Turns the screen and any windows on it (except windows opened by something
other than TechCon or a TechnoBBS node) into an AppIcon.

        The string gadgets in the bevelbox:

        @{b}BBS Task Priority:@{ub}

Indicates/modifies the priority of the TechnoBBS node selected in the
listview.  Enabled only for active nodes.

        @{b}Con Task Priority:@{ub}

Indicates/modifies the priority of the TechCon task.

        @{b}Time Left:@{ub}

Indicates/modifies the time left of the user logged on to the TechnoBBS
node selected in the listview.  -1 indicates unlimited time.  Enabled only
for active nodes.

The Chip, Fast, Date and Time displays are updated every 10 seconds and
should be self-explanatory.

@endnode

@node TechConARexx "TechCon - ARexx"

@{b}Commands:@{ub}

TechCon has an ARexx command port called 'TechCon' via which the following
commands can be accessed:

        @{"     DisableCron     " link TCDisableCron}
        @{"     EnableCron      " link TCEnableCron}
        @{"     ExitCon         " link TCExitCon}
        @{"     NewEvents       " link TCNewEvents}
        @{"     ReadEvents      " link TCReadEvents}
        @{"     SetConPri       " link TCSetConPri}


@{b}Functions:@{ub}

TechCon also adds itself as a function handler for ARexx.  If the function
name doesn't begin with 'Con_', it passes it to the TechnoBBS node
indicated by the value of the first argument (if that node is active).  The
following functions can be used:

        @{"     Con_LineActive  " link TCLineActive}
        @{"     Con_LineStatus  " link TCLineStatus}
        @{"     Con_LineUser    " link TCLineUser}
        @{"     Con_LogOn       " link TCLogOn}
        @{"     Con_MaxNode     " link TCMaxNode}

@endnode

@node Cron "TechCon - Cron feature"

TechCon has an ability to run commands at specified times automatically.
This feature can be configured by creating an ASCII file (using any text
editor), which contains the configuration for an event on each line.  The
line can contain the following keywords, which specify what date/time will
trigger the event:

Min <number>            Minutes (0-59)
Hour <number>           Hours (0-23)
Month <number>          Month (0-11)
Year <number>           Year
DayOfWeek <number>      Day of the week (0-6, 0 = Sunday)
DayOfMon <number>       Day of the month (1-31)
DayOfYear <number>      Day of the year (0-366)

Other accepted keywords are:

Once                    The command will only be run once
Command <string>        The rest of the line is interpreted as the command
                        to run whenever the event is triggered  (must be
                        last)

Example configuration:

Min 0 Command run <>NIL: execute BBS:Scripts/HourEvent
Month 0 Once Command run <>NIL: execute BBS:Scripts/January

This configuration would cause TechCon to execute the 'HourEvent' script
once every hour (every time the minutes of the system time become 0) and
'January' the next time it is January, but only the first time this is
true.  (Except of course if you run TechCon again) If it's January when
TechCon is run, 'January' will be executed immediately, otherwise it will
be executed the first of January at midnight.

@endnode

@node TCSetConPri "TechCon ARexx - SetConPri"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetConPri <priority>

Sets the task priority for TechCon.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetConPri "-5"

@endnode

@node TCDisableCron "TechCon ARexx - DisableCron"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DisableCron

Disables the @{"Cron" link Cron} feature of TechCon.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DisableCron

@endnode

@node TCEnableCron "TechCon ARexx - EnableCron"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          EnableCron

Enables the @{"Cron" link Cron} function of TechCon.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        EnableCron

@endnode

@node TCNewEvents "TechCon ARexx - NewEvents"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          NewEvents

Clears the list of @{"Cron" link Cron} events.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NewEvents

@endnode

@node TCReadEvents "TechCon ARexx - ReadEvents"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ReadEvents "<filename>"

Reads events from <filename> and adds them to the @{"Cron" link Cron} event
list (note that this doesn't clear the list).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ReadEvents "BBS:Cfg/Events.Cfg"

@endnode

@node TCExitCon "TechCon ARexx - ExitCon"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ExitCon

Causes TechCon to try to exit.  If there are nodes active, it will not exit
until the nodes have finished.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ExitCon

@endnode

@node TCLineActive "TechCon ARexx - Con_LineActive"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          PortName = Con_LineActive(<line number>)

Tests if a TechnoBBS node is active.  If it is active, returns the name of
it's ARexx-port, otherwise returns "".

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Ln1Port = Con_LineActive(1)

@endnode

@node TCLogOn "TechCon ARexx - Con_LogOn"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          PortName = Con_LogOn(<line number>)

Activates a TechnoBBS node.  Returns it's ARexx port name.  (The port is
available immediately when this function returns)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Ln1Port = Con_LogOn(1)

@endnode

@node TCLineStatus "TechCon ARexx - Con_LineStatus"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          StatusDesc = Con_LineStatus(<line number>)

Gets the status of a TechnoBBS node, if it is active.  Returns a string
containing a description of the status of the user logged on to the
specified node (ie. what the user is currently doing).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Ln1Status = Con_LineStatus(1)

@endnode

@node TCLineUser "TechCon ARexx - Con_LineUser"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserName = Con_LineUser(<line number>)

Gets the name of the user logged on to a TechnoBBS node, if it is active.
Returns a string containing the name of the user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Ln1User = Con_LineUser(1)

@endnode

@node TCMaxNode "TechCon ARexx - Con_MaxNode"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          maxnodenum = Con_MaxNode()

Returns the highest node number in the system.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        say "The system has "||Con_MaxNode()||" remote nodes"

@endnode

@node TechConCfg "TechCon - Configuration"

The TechCon Configuration file (usually BBS:Cfg/TechCon.Cfg) is a normal
ASCII-file and can be created/edited with a normal text editor.

';' and '#' are identifiers for comment lines, if the first non-blank
character of a line is either of these, the parser skips the line.

If a line begins with a '>', the line is executed as an AmigaDOS command
line after TechCon has finished its startup.

For other lines, the following keywords are valid:

        @{"     BBSDir           " link TCBBSDir}
        @{"     BrokerPri        " link TCBrokerPri}
        @{"     CustomScreen     " link TCCustomScreen}
        @{"     DefaultPubScreen " link TCDefaultPubScreen}
        @{"     DisableLogoff    " link TCDisableLogoff}
        @{"     EditCommand      " link TCEditCommand}
        @{"     EventFile        " link TCEventFile}
        @{"     ExitCommand      " link TCExitCommand}
        @{"     FidoNode         " link TCFidoNode}
        @{"     FileDir          " link TCFileDir}
        @{"     Hotkey           " link TCHotkey}
        @{"     Interleaved      " link TCInterleaved}
        @{"     Laced            " link TCLaced}
        @{"     LaunchCommand    " link TCLaunchCommand}
        @{"     LogFile          " link TCLogFile}
        @{"     LogOnCommand     " link TCLogOnCommand}
        @{"     MailCommand      " link TCMailCommand}
        @{"     MailDir          " link TCMailDir}
        @{"     MaxLine          " link TCMaxLine}
        @{"     MinMem           " link TCMinMem}
        @{"     ModeID           " link TCModeID}
        @{"     Monitor          " link TCMonitor}
        @{"     MsgAreas         " link TCMsgAreas}
        @{"     OpenActive       " link TCOpenActive}
        @{"     OpenAppIcon      " link TCOpenAppIcon}
        @{"     OpenIconified    " link TCOpenIconified}
        @{"     Overscan         " link TCOverscan}
        @{"     Palette          " link TCPalette}
        @{"     PubScreenName    " link TCPubScreenName}
        @{"     Resolution       " link TCResolution}
        @{"     ScreenBehind     " link TCScreenBehind}
        @{"     ScreenDepth      " link TCScreenDepth}
        @{"     ScreenFont       " link TCScreenFont}
        @{"     ScreenFontSize   " link TCScreenFontSize}
        @{"     ScreenHeight     " link TCScreenHeight}
        @{"     ScreenWidth      " link TCScreenWidth}
        @{"     ShanghaiWindows  " link TCShanghaiWindows}
        @{"     TaskPri          " link TCTaskPri}
        @{"     WindowLeft       " link TCWindowLeft}
        @{"     WindowToBack     " link TCWindowToBack}
        @{"     WindowTop        " link TCWindowTop}

@endnode

@node TCDisableLogoff "TechCon Configuration - DisableLogoff"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DisableLogoff

Disables the keyboard shortcut for the 'logoff' gadget.  (Someone
complained about throwing out users by accident... ;--)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Not active

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DisableLogoff

@endnode

@node TCScreenFont "TechCon Configuration - ScreenFont"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ScreenFont <font>

Sets the default font for any screen TechCon opens.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use system default

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ScreenFont LetterGothic.font

@endnode

@node TCScreenFontSize "TechCon Configuration - ScreenFontSize"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ScreenFontSize <height>

Sets the height to use for the font specified by @{"ScreenFont" link TCScreenFont}.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ScreenFontSize 8

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ScreenFontSize 15

@endnode

@node TCMsgAreas "TechCon Configuration - MsgAreas"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MsgAreas <areas>

Sets the number of message areas that the system has.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MsgAreas 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MsgAreas 162

@endnode

@node TCMailDir "TechCon Configuration - MailDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MailDir <path>

Sets the path to the mail-directory, which must have a subdirectory MsgDat
for the systems message data.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MailDir MAIL:

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MailDir SYS:Messages

@endnode

@node TCMailCommand "TechCon Configuration - MailCommand"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MailCommand <command>

Sets the command for TechCon to run when the 'TechMail'-gadget os pressed.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MailCommand run TechMail

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MailCommand run execute BBS:Scripts/DoMail

@endnode

@node TCHotkey "TechCon Configuration - Hotkey"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Hotkey <hotkey>

Sets the hotkey the TechCon commodity will respond to.  (If as an AppIcon,
TechCon will open itself and its screen, otherwise it will just pop up in
front of everything)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Hotkey ctrl alt t

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Hotkey ctrl lcommand c

@endnode

@node TCInterleaved "TechCon Configuration - Interleaved"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Interleaved
                NoInterleaved

Sets whether the interleaved tag will be TRUE for the screen TechCon opens.
This tag is ignored by older operating systems so usually this option
shouldn't cause any problems, but if you experience freezes before TechCon
opens it's custom screen, you might want turning interleaved off.  (This
tag seems to be incompatible with some graphics cards)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Interleaved

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoInterleaved

@endnode

@node TCLaced "TechCon Configuration - Laced"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Laced
                NoLaced

Sets whether TechCon will open an interlaced screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoLaced:

Example         Laced

@endnode

@node TCOverscan "TechCon Configuration - Overscan"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TextOScan
                StandardOScan
                MaxOScan
                VideoOScan                

Sets the overscan mode for the screen TechCon will open.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        TextOScan

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MaxOScan

@endnode

@node TCMonitor "TechCon Configuration - Monitor"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          PAL
                NTSC

Sets the monitor to use for the screen TechCon will open.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        PAL

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NTSC

@endnode

@node TCBrokerPri "TechCon Configuration - BrokerPri"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BrokerPri <priority>

Sets the priority TechCon will use for it's commodities broker.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        BrokerPri 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BrokerPri -10

@endnode

@node TCEditCommand "TechCon Configuration - EditCommand"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          EditCommand <command>

Sets the command to use for activating the user editor.  The argument
string for this option can contain two %s identifiers for a string, the
first will be replaced with the users name to edit, the second with the
public screen name.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        EditCommand run TechUserEd %s -p%s

@{b}Example:@{ub}        EditCommand run execute BBS:Scripts/Edit %s -p%s

See also:       @{"TechUserEd" link TechUserEd}

@endnode

@node TCFidoNode "TechCon Configuration - FidoNode"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FidoNode [[zone:]net/]node[.point]

Sets the default FidoNet address for the system.  Should always be
specified if you have any net areas.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No address set

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FidoNode 170:10/101.0

@endnode

@node TCFileDir "TechCon Configuration - FileDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FileDir <path>

Sets the path for the root of the file base.  There should be a
filearea.dat here but usually you probably won't want to have files in the
root directory, so subdirectories for this may be useful.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        FileDir BBS:Files

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FileDir HD2:Stuff/FileRoot

@endnode

@node TCResolution "TechCon Configuration - Resolution"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          HiRes
                LoRes
                SuperHiRes

Sets the horizontal resolution mode for the screen to be opened in.
(Normally HiRes: 640, LoRes: 320, SuperHiRes: 1280)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        HiRes

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SuperHiRes

@endnode

@node TCCustomScreen "TechCon Configuration - CustomScreen"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          CustomScreen
                NoCustomScreen

CustomScreen tells TechCon to open a screen for the TechCon and TechnoBBS
windows.  The screen will be public.  NoCustomScreen tells TechCon not to
open a screen, the windows will be placed on the default public screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoCustomScreen

@{b}Example:@{ub}        CustomScreen

@endnode

@node TCScreenDepth "TechCon Configuration - ScreenDepth"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ScreenDepth <depth>

Sets the depth of the screen TechCon will open.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ScreenDepth 2

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ScreenDepth 4

@endnode

@node TCScreenWidth "TechCon Configuration - ScreenWidth"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ScreenWidth <width>

Sets the width of the screen TechCon will open.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ScreenWidth -1
                (Uses system default)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ScreenWidth 710

@endnode

@node TCScreenHeight "TechCon Configuration - ScreenHeight"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ScreenHeight <height>

Sets the height of the screen TechCon will open.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ScreenHeight -1
                (Uses system default)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ScreenHeight 280

@endnode

@node TCPalette "TechCon Configuration - Palette"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Palette <colors>

Sets the palette to use for the screen (if the screen is used).  <colors>
must contain the RGB values for each color entry in the palette (in hex) in
order (no identifiers for the entry to store the RGB value in).  You can
also define pen types (0-8) for each entry to represent, but if you define
any, you must have them all somewhere.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use system default palette

Example #1:     Palette 000 fff
                (2 Colors, no pens)

Example #2:     Palette 0007 C00 0C0 CC0 00C C0C 0CC AAA152 666046 F00 0F0
                FF0 00F F0F8 0FF FFF3    (Note: Should be on one line)
                (16 colors, pen types defined, this palette looks pretty
                good as long as your machine can handle a 16-color screen
                fast enough (an AGA system or an 030/040 w/CPUBlit))

@endnode

@node TCOpenActive "TechCon Configuration - OpenActive"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OpenActive
                NoOpenActive

OpenActive tells TechCon to activate it's window when it is opened.
NoOpenActive won't activate the window.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoOpenActive

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OpenActive

@endnode

@node TCMaxLine "TechCon Configuration - MaxLine"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MaxLine <highest node number>

Sets the number of remote nodes for the BBS to use.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MaxLine 1

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MaxLine 10

@endnode

@node TCScreenBehind "TechCon Configuration - ScreenBehind"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ScreenBehind
                NoScreenBehind

ScreenBehind causes TechCon to open it's screen behind any other screens
open at that time.  NoScreenBehind causes it to open it in front of the
other screens.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ScreenBehind

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoScreenBehind

@endnode

@node TCWindowToBack "TechCon Configuration - WindowToBack"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowToBack
                NoWindowToBack

WindowToBack tells TechCon to move it's window behind other windows on
whatever screen it opens on immediately after opening it.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        WindowToBack

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoWindowToBack

@endnode

@node TCWindowLeft "TechCon Configuration - WindowLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowLeft <offset>

Sets the offset of the TechCon window from the left edge of the screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Calculate center of the screen

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowLeft 10

@endnode

@node TCWindowTop "TechCon Configuration - WindowTop"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowTop <offset>

Sets the offset of the TechCon window from the top edge of the screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Calculate center of the screen

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowTop 10

@endnode

@node TCEventFile "TechCon Configuration - EventFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          EventFile <filename>

Tells TechCon to read <filename> as a configuration for its @{"CRON" link Cron}
feature.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No timed events

@{b}Example:@{ub}        EventFile BBS:Cfg/Events.Cfg

@endnode

@node TCTaskPri "TechCon Configuration - TaskPri"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TaskPri <priority>

Sets the priority TechCon will set its process to.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        TaskPri -1

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TaskPri 1

@endnode

@node TCBBSDir "TechCon Configuration - BBSDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BBSDir <directory>

Sets the main BBS directory to use.  Everything without a full path is
assumed to be in relation to this directory.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        BBSDir BBS:

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BBSDir HD1:TechBBS

@endnode

@node TCOpenIconified "TechCon Configuration - OpenIconified"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OpenIconified
                NoOpenIconified

OpenIconified tells TechCon to zip it's window immediately after opening
this.  NoOpenIconified leaves the window in full size.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        OpenIconified

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoOpenIconified

@endnode

@node TCExitCommand "TechCon Configuration - ExitCommand"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ExitCommand <commandline>

If specified, TechCon will run <commandline> as an AmigaDOS command while
exiting.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No command is run

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ExitCommand execute s:shutdownscript

@endnode

@node TCLogOnCommand "TechCon Configuration - LogOnCommand"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogOnCommand <commandline>

Sets the command used to activate a TechnoBBS node when a logon is
requested from ARexx.  A %u in the commandline-string will be replaced with
the node number being activated.  (Whatever the command is, it must run the
TechnoBBS executable giving it the correct node number as an argument!)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        LogOnCommand run TechnoBBS %u

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogOnCommand run execute s:Node%uScript

In the above example, the scripts should contain at least the following:

Node0Script:
run TechnoBBS 0

Node1Script:
run TechnoBBS 1

etc.

@endnode

@node TCLaunchCommand "TechCon Configuration - LaunchCommand"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LaunchCommand <commandline>

Sets the command used to activate a TechnoBBS node when a logon is
requested from the launch-button on the TechCon window.  A %u in the
commandline-string will be replaced with the node number being activated.
(Whatever the command is, it must run the TechnoBBS executable giving it
the correct node number as an argument!)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use whatever @{"LogOnCommand" link TCLogOnCommand} is using

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LaunchCommand run execute s:Node%uScript

In the above example, the scripts should contain at least the following:

Node0Script:
run TechnoBBS 0

Node1Script:
run TechnoBBS 1

etc.

@endnode

@node TCLogFile "TechCon Configuration - LogFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogFile <filename>

Sets the file to log information about TechCon operation in.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No logfile kept

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogFile BBS:Logs/TechCon.log

@endnode

@node TCPubScreenName "TechCon Configuration - PubScreenName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          PubScreenName <name>

Sets the name TechCon will use for it's public screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        PubScreenName TechScreen

@{b}Example:@{ub}        PubScreenName ThisIsAPublicScreen

@endnode

@node TCDefaultPubScreen "TechCon Configuration - DefaultPubScreen"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DefaultPubScreen
                NoDefaultPubScreen

DefaultPubScreen tells TechCon to set the public screen it opens as the
systems default public screen.  NoDefaultPubScreen leaves whatever is
default before running TechCon as the default.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoDefaultPubScreen

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DefaultPubScreen

@endnode

@node TCShanghaiWindows "TechCon Configuration - ShanghaiWindows"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ShanghaiWindows
                NoShanghaiWindows

ShanghaiWindows causes TechCon to set the Shanghai mode on (ie., windows
intended for the Workbench-screen will open on the default public screen).
NoShanghaiWindows will leave this mode as it is when TechCon is run.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoShanghaiWindows

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ShanghaiWindows

@endnode

@node TCModeID "TechCon Configuration - ModeID"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ModeID <id>

Sets the screen mode id for the custom screen TechCon will open.  Most of
the specifications for the mode can be set using the other options, but if
you want to use a custom monitor type you can use this to override the
other settings.  If you specify a hex id, the identifier for hex is '0x'.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use other settings

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ModeID 0x000a9000
                (Sets DblPAL hires)

@endnode

@node TCMinMem "TechCon Configuration - MinMem"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MinMem <memory>

When the amount of free memory goes below <memory>, TechCon will first
attempt a flush to free some memory, then turn on the @{"LowMem Mode" link
LowMem}.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MinMem 262144

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MinMem 1048576

@endnode

@node TCOpenAppIcon "TechCon Configuration - OpenAppIcon"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OpenAppIcon
                NoOpenAppIcon

OpenAppIcon will cause TechCon not to open any screens and/or windows, only
an AppIcon.  Once the AppIcon is double-clicked, everything will open as
configured.  NoOpenAppIcon will let everything open normally during
startup.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoOpenAppIcon

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OpenAppIcon

@endnode

@node TechnoBBS "TechnoBBS"

@{b}@{i}TechnoBBS @{ub}@{ui}is the actual BBS-software and is run for each node.  You can
have almost any number of TechnoBBS nodes active as long as you don't run
out of memory.  You need to have TechCon running to be able to run the main
TechnoBBS executable.

The main TechnoBBS executable should only be run by TechCon, though it can
be run directly (as long as TechCon is active).

To run TechnoBBS directly (or to configure how TechCon will it):

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechnoBBS <node number>

When TechCon runs TechnoBBS, it will set its current directory to the main
BBS-directory.  TechnoBBS will always look for its configuration as
'Cfg/BBS<node>.Cfg' so you should have a configuration by that name in the
'Cfg'-subdirectory of the main BBS-directory.

If you run TechnoBBS manually, you should have the main BBS-directory (or
some other directory with a subdirectory 'Cfg' containing the necessary
configuration file) as your current directory.

The TechnoBBS executable is pure and it is recommended that you resident it
if you're running a BBS with more than one node or if you log on to the
local node often.

Once run, TechnoBBS may open a window, depending on its configuration and
the current state of TechCon.  It will send the following to the remote
(except when running node number 0, which is always the local node) and the
console (if it has a window open):

<title and copyright information>
Registered to <your name> (<serial number>)

(or if you haven't registered, it will display '[UNREGISTERED]' instead of
'Registered to <your name> (<serial number>)')

After this TechnoBBS will enter an idle state to wait for input from
various sources until something happens.  Usually you should have an ARexx
script sending something to TechnoBBS at this point.  All control of
TechnoBBS (except timeout) is dependent on external sources (TechCon, the
menus, ARexx) and you probably wouldn't accomplish much by just running
TechnoBBS.

        @{"  TechnoBBS - Configuration  " link TechnoBBSCfg}
        @{"  TechnoBBS - Interface      " link TechnoBBSWin}
        @{"  TechnoBBS - ARexx          " link TechnoBBSARexx}

@endnode

@node TechnoBBSCfg "TechnoBBS - Configuration"

The TechnoBBS Configuration file (usually BBS:Cfg/BBS<node>.Cfg) is a
normal ASCII-file and can be created/edited with a normal text editor.

';' and '#' are identifiers for comment lines, if the first non-blank
character of a line is either of these, the parser skips the line.

If a line begins with a '>', the line is executed as an AmigaDOS command
line after TechnoBBS has finished its startup.

For other lines, the following keywords are valid:

        @{"     7Wire           " link TB7Wire}
        @{"     ASCIIBuffer     " link TBASCIIBuffer}
        @{"     Backdrop        " link TBBackdrop}
        @{"     BiDirOpts       " link TBBiDirOpts}
        @{"     ChatOffString   " link TBChatOffString}
        @{"     ChatOnString    " link TBChatOnString}
        @{"     CmdHistory      " link TBCmdHistory}
        @{"     ConsoleCharSet  " link TBConsoleCharSet}
        @{"     DefUserCatalog  " link TBDefUserCatalog}
        @{"     DefXPRBuffer    " link TBDefXPRBuffer}
        @{"     DeleteFailed    " link TBDeleteFailed}
        @{"     Device          " link TBDevice}
        @{"     FastCon         " link TBFastCon}
        @{"     FidoNode        " link TBFidoNode}
        @{"     FileCheck       " link TBFileCheck}
        @{"     Font            " link TBFont}
        @{"     FontSize        " link TBFontSize}
        @{"     FreeChatTime    " link TBFreeChatTime}
        @{"     FreeUploadTime  " link TBFreeUploadTime}
        @{"     IgnoreDCD       " link TBIgnoreDCD}
        @{"     Keymap          " link TBKeymap}
        @{"     Locale          " link TBLocale}
        @{"     LogFile         " link TBLogFile}
        @{"     LogOnTime       " link TBLogOnTime}
        @{"     MaxDescLines    " link TBMaxDescLines}
        @{"     MaxXPRBuffer    " link TBMaxXPRBuffer}
        @{"     MinUploadSpace  " link TBMinUploadSpace}
        @{"     ModemHang       " link TBModemHang}
        @{"     OpenActive      " link TBOpenActive}
        @{"     OpenIconified   " link TBOpenIconified}
        @{"     OriginString    " link TBOriginString}
        @{"     Protocol        " link TBProtocol}
        @{"     PubName         " link TBPubName}
        @{"     SerBaud         " link TBSerBaud}
        @{"     SerialCharSet   " link TBSerialCharSet}
        @{"     Shared          " link TBShared}
        @{"     SourceCharSet   " link TBSourceCharSet}
        @{"     StoreUploader   " link TBStoreUploader}
        @{"     SysOpAvail      " link TBSysOpAvail}
        @{"     SysOpName       " link TBSysOpName}
        @{"     TaskPri         " link TBTaskPri}
        @{"     TempSendDir     " link TBTempSendDir}
        @{"     TimeOut         " link TBTimeOut}
        @{"     Unit            " link TBUnit}
        @{"     Window          " link TBWindow}
        @{"     WindowHeight    " link TBWindowHeight}
        @{"     WindowLeft      " link TBWindowLeft}
        @{"     WindowToBack    " link TBWindowToBack}
        @{"     WindowTop       " link TBWindowTop}
        @{"     WindowWidth     " link TBWindowWidth}

@endnode

@node TBTempSendDir "TechnoBBS Configuration - TempSendDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TempSendDir <path>

If specified, all files being sent to the user using an XPR protocol are
copied to <path> before being sent and deleted after the transfer.  If you
set a directory for this option, make sure the device the path is on has
lots of space, otherwise file transfers may fail.

There are at least two situations in which it might be a good idea to use
this option:

 - If you are running a BBS with several nodes and a CD-ROM.  (Simultaneous
   transfers off a CD-ROM can be slow)

 - If you have lots of memory and a really slow hard disk.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Send directly from the file area

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TempSendDir Work:Tmp

@endnode

@node TBBiDirOpts "TechnoBBS Configuration - BiDirOpts"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BiDirOpts <protocol name> <opts>

Sets the protocol options to be used when performing
@{"bi-directional file transfers" link bixfer}.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BiDirOpts DModem XY,LY,IY,B8192

@endnode

@node TBMaxDescLines "TechnoBBS Configuration - MaxDescLines"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MaxDescLines <lines>

Sets the maximum lines to use for long descriptions.  If set to 0, long
descriptions can't be entered manually for uploaded files or using the
@{"ChgDesc" link TBChgDesc} command.

Note:  Though the MaxDescLines value isn't actually limited to anything,
storage and displaying of the description is.  You should set this value to
something small enough to prevent any descriptions from being larger than a
users screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MaxDescLines 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MaxDescLines 20

@endnode

@node TBFastCon "TechnoBBS Configuration - FastCon"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FastCon
                NoFastCon

Causes TechnoBBS to open the 'fastcon.device' for output instead of the
usual 'console.device'.  If you use this option, you should first manually
copy the device to your devs: directory.  (This is not done by the install
script to prevent people from "accidentally" using the device)

Warning:  You must have the node you use this option for on a backdrop
window, the screen must be in a standard Amiga mode (this device doesn't
support screen modes of graphics cards) and you must have an ECS/AGA
blitter.  Even if you have all this, this option is NOT recommended, since
the fastcon.device is far from bug-free.  (I'll try to fix it in the
future)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoFastCon

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FastCon

@endnode

@node TBStoreUploader "TechnoBBS Configuration - StoreUploader"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          StoreUploader
                NoStoreUploader

Having StoreUploader set will cause TechnoBBS to store the name of the
person who uploads a file in 'filext.dat'.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoStoreUploader

@{b}Example:@{ub}        StoreUploader

@endnode

@node TBFreeChatTime "TechnoBBS Configuration - FreeChatTime"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FreeChatTime
                NoFreeChatTime

Having FreeChatTime enabled will automatically turn the users time off
(activate the "free time" in the menu) when chatting with the SysOp.  After
the chat, the menu item will return to whatever state it was in before the
chat.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoFreeChatTime

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FreeChatTime

@endnode

@node TBDefXPRBuffer "TechnoBBS Configuration - DefXPRBuffer"
@{ub}Usage:@{ub}          DefXPRBuffer <size>

Sets the default size (in bytes) of the two output buffers to allocate for
XPR transfers.  Setting this and @{"MaxXPRBuffer" link TBMaxXPRBuffer} to zero will disable this
feature.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        DefXPRBuffer 1024

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DefXPRBuffer 8192

@endnode

@node TBMaxXPRBuffer "TechnoBBS Configuration - MaxXPRBuffer"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MaxXPRBuffer <size>

Sets the maximum size (in bytes) of the two output buffers to allocate for
XPR transfers.  Whenever the XPR library sends an amount of data that is
larger than the size of the allocated buffer but smaller than the maximum
size, a new buffer will be allocated.  If the data is larger than the
maximum size, synchronous output will be used.  Setting this and
@{"DefXPRBuffer" link TBDefXPRBuffer} to zero will disable buffered output.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MaxXPRBuffer 65536

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MaxXPRBuffer 1048576

@endnode

@node TBBackdrop "TechnoBBS Configuration - Backdrop"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Backdrop
                NoBackdrop

Sets whether TechnoBBS will use a backdrop window on its own screen.  If
backdrop is set, whenever the window is closed, an AppIcon will be opened
instead.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoBackdrop

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Backdrop

@endnode

@node TBPubName "TechnoBBS Configuration - PubName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          PubName <name>

If PubName and @{"Backdrop" link TBBackdrop} are specified, the opened screen will be a public
screen by the name set by PubName.  Make sure that the name is unique!

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Not a public screen

@{b}Example:@{ub}        PubName TechNode1

@endnode

@node TB7Wire "TechnoBBS Configuration - 7Wire"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          7Wire
                No7Wire

Sets whether TechnoBBS will set the 7-Wire handshaking on for the device
it's using.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        7Wire

@{b}Example:@{ub}        No7Wire

@endnode

@node TBASCIIBuffer "TechnoBBS Configuration - ASCIIBuffer"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ASCIIBuffer <length>

Sets the length of the buffer TechnoBBS will write serial (and console)
input to (if it isn't needed immediately).  If you set the length to zero,
no buffer will be used.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ASCIIBuffer 512

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ASCIIBuffer 1024

@endnode

@node TBChatOffString "TechnoBBS Configuration - ChatOffString"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ChatOffString <string>

Sets the string TechnoBBS will output when the chat mode is exited.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ChatOffString End of chat

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ChatOffString The SysOp ran away..

@endnode

@node TBChatOnString "TechnoBBS Configuration - ChatOnString"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ChatOnString <string>

Sets the string TechnoBBS will output when the chat mode is entered.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ChatOnString Entering chat with the SysOp

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ChatOnString WATCH OUT!! THE SYSOP IS HERE!!

@endnode

@node TBCmdHistory "TechnoBBS Configuration - CmdHistory"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          CmdHistory <lines>

Sets the number of lines of command line history to keep for
AskInput-requests.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        CmdHistory 256

@{b}Example:@{ub}        CmdHistory 8192

@endnode

@node TBConsoleCharSet "TechnoBBS Configuration - ConsoleCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ConsoleCharSet <charset>

Sets the character set to use for the console.  This should be set to the
character set the selected font & keymap for the console represent.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ConsoleCharSet ISO

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ConsoleCharSet IBM

@endnode

@node TBDefUserCatalog "TechnoBBS Configuration - DefUserCatalog"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DefUserCatalog <language>

Sets the default language catalog to use.  Starting with version 0.84
(17-Dec-93) this is a textfile containing the strings separated by ctrl-a
characters (ascii 1).  An attempt to load String/<language> is made if this
is set.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        User internal strings (english).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DefUserCatalog suomi

@endnode

@node TBDeleteFailed "TechnoBBS Configuration - DeleteFailed"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DeleteFailed
                NoDeleteFailed

Sets whether files that are uploaded, but fail, are deleted.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoDeleteFailed

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DeleteFailed

@endnode

@node TBDevice "TechnoBBS Configuration - Device"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Device <device name>

Sets the device for TechnoBBS to use for remote I/O.  Has no effect on the
local node.  If you only have the default internal serial port you should
probably have this left to serial.device.  If you have more, you will
probably want to configure this to the driver of your extra serial ports.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Device serial.device

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Device moreports.device

@endnode

@node TBFidoNode "TechnoBBS Configuration - FidoNode"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FidoNode [[zone:]net/]node[.point]

Sets the default FidoNet node number for your BBS.  This is overrided by
the AKA of a message area for processing done in that area.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No address

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FidoNode 170:10/101.0

@endnode

@node TBFileCheck "TechnoBBS Configuration - FileCheck"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FileCheck <command>

Sets a command to check uploaded files with.  Usually this will be a script
(or executable) that checks the archive integrity, tests if the contents is
infected with a virus etc.  If the return code of this command is non-zero,
the file is not accepted to the BBS (and will also be deleted from the
users directory if @{"DeleteFailed" link TBDeleteFailed} is true).

Oops..  In documentation versions earlier than 0.89 I forgot to mention
that you must use a %s to indicate where you want the file name to be given
in the command line.

Starting with TechnoBBS 0.89 you can use this check command to set a long
description and uploader name for the file.  If your file checking script
leaves a file by the same name as the file being checked with a
".desc" appended, that will be used for the files long description.  If a
file with ".upload" appended is found, it is used as the name of the
uploader of the file.

Note:  The file check can't call any TechnoBBS ARexx commands or functions,
since it is run synchronously to make it possible to know what the return
code is.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No checking

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FileCheck BBS:Rexx/Checkfile.rexx %s

@endnode

@node TBFont "TechnoBBS Configuration - Font"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Font <name>

Sets the font to use for the console.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use the system default

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Font LetterGothic.font

@endnode

@node TBFontSize "TechnoBBS Configuration - FontSize"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FontSize <size>

Sets the height of the font to use for the console (if a font name is
specified for @{"Font" link TBFont}).

@{b}Default:@{ub}        FontSize 8

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FontSize 11

@endnode

@node TBFreeUploadTime "TechnoBBS Configuration - FreeUploadTime"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FreeUploadTime
                NoFreeUploadTime

If true, will not decrease a users time while the user is uploading.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoFreeUploadTime

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FreeUploadTime

@endnode

@node TBIgnoreDCD "TechnoBBS Configuration - IgnoreDCD"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          IgnoreDCD
                NoIgnoreDCD

If true, the DCD (Data Carrier Detect) of the serial device (or equivalent,
as configured) is ignored (ie. TechnoBBS will not disconnect if the carrier
is lost).  This should only be used if your DCD is disfunctional (problems
with your serial port, modem or a special device).  Has no effect on the
local node.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoIgnoreDCD

@{b}Example:@{ub}        IgnoreDCD

@endnode

@node TBKeymap "TechnoBBS Configuration - Keymap"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Keymap <name>

Sets the keymap to use for the console.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use system default

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Keymap usa2

@endnode

@node TBLocale "TechnoBBS Configuration - Locale"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Locale <language>

Sets the locale (this should not be confused with a catalog) to use.  This
may have some minor effect on string formatting.

NOTE: Won't do anything if the locale.library isn't installed on your
system.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use system default

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Locale suomi

@endnode

@node TBLogFile "TechnoBBS Configuration - LogFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogFile <filename>

Sets the file to append log entrys for this node to.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Don't keep a log

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogFile BBS:Logs/Node1.log

@endnode

@node TBLogOnTime "TechnoBBS Configuration - LogOnTime"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogOnTime <minutes>

Sets the time (in minutes) that is specified for the time left before
anyone logs on (so that a user has this much time to watch all your neat
title screens and type in his name and password)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        LogOnTime 5

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogOnTime 30

@endnode

@node TBMinUploadSpace "TechnoBBS Configuration - MinUploadSpace"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MinUploadSpace <bytes>

Sets the minimum space that has to be avaiable on the device to enable
uploading.  This should be higher than the sum of the length largest file
you expect anyone to upload and the amount of space you wish to keep for
your own use.  The upload space is tested for the device you have the
file area being uploaded to on.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MinUploadSpace 1048576

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MinUploadSpace 20971520

@endnode

@node TBModemHang "TechnoBBS Configuration - ModemHang"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ModemHang <string>

Sets the string to send to the modem when exiting.  A '^' followed by a
capital letter (or a symbol, since some symbols also have control codes)
will result in the control code equivalent to the letter (its ASCII value
minus 32).  A '~' will produce a delay.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ModemHang ~~~+++~~~ATH^M~

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ModemHang

@endnode

@node TBOpenActive "TechnoBBS Configuration - OpenActive"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OpenActive
                NoOpenActive

Sets whether TechnoBBS will activate the window it opens.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoOpenActive

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OpenActive

@endnode

@node TBOpenIconified "TechnoBBS Configuration - OpenIconified"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OpenIconified
                NoOpenIconified

Sets whether TechnoBBS will zip the window it opens after opening it.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoOpenIconified

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OpenIconified

@endnode

@node TBOriginString "TechnoBBS Configuration - OriginString"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OriginString <string>

Sets the default origin string for echo areas.  Overrided by an origin
specified for a specific message area.  The node address is appended
automatically.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No origin string

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OriginString TechnoBBS Development Center

@endnode

@node TBProtocol "TechnoBBS Configuration - Protocol"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Protocol <protocol> <library> <options>

Sets the library name and options to associate with a protocol.  You should
specify this for each protocol you will be using.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No protocols configured

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Protocol ZModem xprzmodem.library TC,OR,B16,F0,E10,AY,DN,KY,SN,RN,P

@endnode

@node TBSerBaud "TechnoBBS Configuration - SerBaud"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SerBaud <rate>

Sets the baud rate to use for communication with the device configured
using the @{"Device" link TBDevice} keyword.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use whatever baud rate the device is set to when opened

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SerBaud 57600

@endnode

@node TBSerialCharSet "TechnoBBS Configuration - SerialCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SerialCharSet <charset>

Sets the default character set to use for the remote.  This is changed to
whatever a user has configured for their character set when a user is
loaded.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        SerialCharSet ISO

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SerialCharSet IBM

@endnode

@node TBShared "TechnoBBS Configuration - Shared"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Shared
                NoShared

Sets whether the remote device will be opened in the shared access-mode.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Shared

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoShared

@endnode

@node TBSourceCharSet "TechnoBBS Configuration - SourceCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SourceCharSet <charset>

Sets the character set to convert from when sending internal/catalog
strings, textfiles etc.  This should usually be set to 'ISO' and never to
any character set that might convert important characters such as '['
(which is part of ANSI escape-sequences) to something else.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        SourceCharSet ISO

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SourceCharSet IBM

@endnode

@node TBSysOpAvail "TechnoBBS Configuration - SysOpAvail"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SysOpAvail
                NoSysOpAvail

Sets the default SysOp availability.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        SysOpAvail

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoSysOpAvail

@endnode

@node TBSysOpName "TechnoBBS Configuration - SysOpName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SysOpName <name>

Sets the name of the SysOp of the BBS.  This name is used on the top bar of
the split-screen chat when chatting with the SysOp and for replacing the
username "SysOp" if a messages is posted to that name.  It doesn't have to
be your real name though.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        SysOpName SysOp

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SysOpName The mighty ruler of this BBS

@endnode

@node TBTaskPri "TechnoBBS Configuration - TaskPri"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TaskPri <priority>

Sets the task priority that this TechnoBBS node will set for itself when
run.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        TaskPri 1

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TaskPri 0

@endnode

@node TBTimeOut "TechnoBBS Configuration - TimeOut"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TimeOut <minutes>

Sets the number of minutes TechnoBBS will let a user be inactive (ie. no
remote/console input) before disconnecting.  This value is not accurate,
since it is only tested every minute.  A user on the local node is never
logged off due to an inactivity timeout.  A value of zero disables the
feature.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        TimeOut 5

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TimeOut 3

@endnode

@node TBUnit "TechnoBBS Configuration - Unit"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Unit <unit>

Sets the unit number to open the remote device specified by @{"Device" link TBDevice} as.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Unit 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Unit 1

@endnode

@node TBWindow "TechnoBBS Configuration - Window"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Window
                NoWindow

Sets whether TechnoBBS will open a console window by default.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Window

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoWindow

@endnode

@node TBWindowHeight "TechnoBBS Configuration - WindowHeight"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowHeight <height>

Sets the height of the window TechnoBBS will open.  This is the inner
height of the window, it doesn't include the borders.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        WindowHeight 256

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowHeight 480

@endnode

@node TBWindowLeft "TechnoBBS Configuration - WindowLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowLeft <offset>

Sets the offset of the window from the left edge of the screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        WindowLeft 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowLeft 20

@endnode

@node TBWindowToBack "TechnoBBS Configuration - WindowToBack"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowToBack
                NoWindowToBack

Sets whether TechnoBBS will put it's window behind other windows after
opening it.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoWindowToBack

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowToBack

@endnode

@node TBWindowTop "TechnoBBS Configuration - WindowTop"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowTop <offset>

Sets the offset of the window from the top of the screen.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        WindowTop 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowTop 12

@endnode

@node TBWindowWidth "TechnoBBS Configuration - WindowWidth"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WindowWidth <width>

Sets the width of the window TechnoBBS will open.  This is the inner width
of the window, it doesn't include the borders.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        WindowWidth 640

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WindowWidth 800

@endnode

@node TechnoBBSArexx "TechnoBBS - ARexx"

@{b}Commands:@{ub}

Each TechnoBBS node has an ARexx command port.  You can get the name of the
port from TechCon.

        @{"     AddFile                 " link TBAddFile}
        @{"     ChgDesc                 " link TBChgDesc}
        @{"     ChgFileArea             " link TBChgFileArea}
