        @{"     GetFileArea             " link TBGetFileArea}
        @{"     GetFilePath             " link TBGetFilePath}
        @{"     GetFileRatio            " link TBGetFileRatio}
        @{"     GetFilesDownloaded      " link TBGetFilesDownloaded}
        @{"     GetFilesLeft            " link TBGetFilesLeft}
        @{"     GetFilesUploaded        " link TBGetFilesUploaded}
        @{"     GetHighRead             " link TBGetHighRead}
        @{"     GetHighMsg              " link TBGetHighMsg}
        @{"     GetHotkey               " link TBGetHotkey}
        @{"     GetLowMsg               " link TBGetLowMsg}
        @{"     GetMask                 " link TBGetMask}
        @{"     GetMaxTimeBank          " link TBGetMaxTimeBank}
        @{"     GetMessages             " link TBGetMessages}
        @{"     GetMsgArea              " link TBGetMsgArea}
        @{"     GetMsgAreaName          " link TBGetMsgAreaName}
        @{"     GetPassword             " link TBGetPassword}
        @{"     GetSimpleTerm           " link TBGetSimpleTerm}
        @{"     GetSlowTerm             " link TBGetSlowTerm}
        @{"     GetStripAll             " link TBGetStripAll}
        @{"     GetStripCols            " link TBGetStripCols}
        @{"     GetTerminalLines        " link TBGetTerminalLines}
        @{"     GetTimeBank             " link TBGetTimeBank}
        @{"     GetTimeCall             " link TBGetTimeCall}
        @{"     GetTimeDay              " link TBGetTimeDay}
        @{"     GetTimeLeft             " link TBGetTimeLeft}
        @{"     GetTotalCalls           " link TBGetTotalCalls}
        @{"     GetUserAccess           " link TBGetUserAccess}
        @{"     GetUserCharSet          " link TBGetUserCharSet}
        @{"     GetUserExtension        " link TBGetUserExtension}
        @{"     GetUserLanguage         " link TBGetUserLanguage}
        @{"     GetUserMisc             " link TBGetUserMisc}
        @{"     GetUserName             " link TBGetUserName}
        @{"     GetUserPath             " link TBGetUserPath}
        @{"     GetUserProtocol         " link TBGetUserProtocol}
        @{"     GetUserTimeLeft         " link TBGetUserTimeLeft}
        @{"     GetYesNo                " link TBGetYesNo}
        @{"     HasMsgAcc               " link TBHasMsgAcc}
        @{"     MessageCheck            " link TBMessageCheck}
        @{"     ReceiveFiles            " link TBReceiveFiles}
        @{"     SearchMessages          " link TBSearchMessages}
        @{"     SendFiles               " link TBSendFiles}
        @{"     SetUserMisc             " link TBSetUserMisc}
        @{"     SIGName                 " link TBSIGName}
        @{"     SIGtoReal               " link TBSIGtoReal}

@endnode

@node TBDelFile "TechnoBBS ARexx - DelFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DelFile <filespec>

Deletes files in the current area matching <filespec>, which can be a
pattern or a numeric file specification.

Warning: This deletes the actual file from disk (if possible)!  It doesn't
ask you if you're sure, so be careful.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DelFile #?

@endnode

@node TBMoveFile "TechnoBBS ARexx - MoveFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MoveFile <areapath>, <filespec>

Moves a file from the current file area to another.

<areapath> is the directory (this means the actual AmigaDOS directories)
path from the current file area to the destination area.  <filespec> is
either a pattern (which can just be a plain filename) or a numeric file
specification.

If anything goes wrong, the file is left as is, so you can't accidentally
move a file to nowhere.

Note: You should call @{"SaveExt" link TBSaveExt} after you have moved files.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MoveFile /Textfiles, 5-10

@endnode

@node TBReWriteMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - ReWriteMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ReWriteMsg <msg num>

Enables you to "edit" the actual contents of a message.  What it actually
does is the following:

Loads the message <msg num>.  If the user has good enough access (either
message editing/killing/reading private access or the message loaded is
written by this user), activates the message editor with the loaded message
already on-sceen.  When the message editor saves the message, it is saved
normally, and the old message is killed.  (If the new message is aborted,
the old one will not be killed)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ReWriteMsg 162

@endnode

@node TBConvertMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - ConvertMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ConvertMsg <msg num> <charset>

Converts message number <msg num> in the current area from <charset> to
ISO.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ConvertMsg 1234 IBM

@endnode

@node TBDlAndReceive "TechnoBBS ARexx - DlAndReceive"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DlAndReceive

This is a combination of the @{"Upload" link TBUpload} and @{"Download" link TBDownload} (w/MARKEDONLY option)
commands.  To use this command the user must first mark any files to
download, select the file area to upload files to and then call the
DlAndReceive command.  The output and prompt will be identical to a
Download "MARKEDONLY" command.  After the transfer a report of the files
downloaded (sent to the user) will be sent and after that the uploaded
files will be checked.

This command requires a @{"bi-directional file transfer protocol" link bixfer}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DlAndReceive

@endnode

@node bixfer "XPR 2.001"

Uploading and downloading files simultaneously requires a bi-directional
file transfer protocol.  XPR 2.0 does not allow bi-directional protocols to
be implemented easily, some modifications are required for this and are
made possible by the XPR 2.001 extended specifications, which are
unofficial but fully compatible with XPR 2.0 protocols and now supported by
TechnoBBS.  The only publicly released XPR 2.001 protocol known to me is
DModem (versions 2.2 and above should actually be functional).

File transfers have been successfully tested using the following setup:

TechnoBBS 0.90 (beta) running on an A4000/030, using xprdmodem.library 2.2,
init strings "XY,LY,IY,B2048" and "XY,LY,IY,B8192" have been tested.

                                     ^
                                     |
                        14400 (V.32bis) connection
                                     |
                                     V

DreamTerm 1.3 running on A1200 and A3000 (25MHz) machines, using
xprdmodem.library 2.2, I'm not sure of the init strings, one of them was
"XY,LY,IN,B2048".

Transfers in only one direction at a time and both directions
simultaneously were successful and provided good throughput (cps rates
mostly between 1600 and 1700 using packed files, with a combined
send/receive throughput of more than 3200 cps).  Combined throughput using
textfiles with lots of repeating strings should be capable of exceeding
11000 cps with a DTE of 57600 at both ends and a 14400 (V.32bis) connection
with LAP-M error correction and V.42 data compression.

@endnode

@node TBSaveExt "TechnoBBS ARexx - SaveExt"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SaveExt

Sends a message to TechCon telling it to save all the filext.dat data of
the file areas.  This may take a while, so you should only call this when
it is absolutely necessary.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SaveExt

@endnode

@node TBSetUploader "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUploader"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUploader <filename>, <uploader>

Sets the uploader field of a file.  To store the change you must use
@{"SaveExt" link TBSaveExt} after this (before doing an update filelist or exiting TechCon).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUploader AskInput(1, "Filename: ", "", 40)||", "||AskInput(1, "Uploader: ", "", 36)

@endnode

@node TBChgDesc "TechnoBBS ARexx - ChgDesc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ChgDesc <filename>

If the file is found, prompts to enter a new long description for the file.
This is recommended for SysOp use only.  To store the change you must use
@{"SaveExt" link TBSaveExt} after this (before doing an update filelist or exiting TechCon).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ChgDesc AskInput(1, "Enter filename: ", "", 40)

@endnode

@node TBSIGName "TechnoBBS ARexx - SIGName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          name = SIGName(<node>, <sig>)

Returns the name of a SIG.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Current: "||SIGName(1, CurrentSIG(1))

@endnode

@node TBSIGtoReal "TechnoBBS ARexx - SIGtoReal"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          real = SIGtoReal(<node>, <area>)

Given the area number of a message area within the current SIG, this will
return the actual number of the message area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Area "||area||" ("||SIGtoReal(1, area)||")"

@endnode

@node TBCurrentSIG "TechnoBBS ARexx - CurrentSIG"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          sig = CurrentSIG(<node>)

Returns the number of the SIG a user is currently in, or 0 if the user
hasn't selected one.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "SIG: "||CurrentSig(1)

@endnode

@node TBSelectSIGArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - SelectSIGArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SelectSIGArea [<area>]

Enables the user to select a message area within the current SIG.  If no
area number is given, this will list the areas available and prompt the
user to select one.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SelectSIGArea

@endnode

@node TBSelectSIG "TechnoBBS ARexx - SelectSIG"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SelectSIG [<sig>]

Enables the user to select a SIG (i.e. a group of message areas).  If no
sig number is given, this will list the SIGs available and prompt the user
to select one.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SelectSIG

@endnode

@node TBLoadFileMark "TechnoBBS ARexx - LoadFileMark"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LoadFileMark

Loads the users marked files from the file called "FileMark.dat" in the
users directory.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LoadFileMark

@endnode

@node TBAddFile "TechnoBBS ARexx - AddFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          AddFile <filename>

Adds a file to the list of files to send using the @{"SendFiles" link TBSendFiles} function.  The
list can be cleared using @{"ClearFiles" link TBClearFiles}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        AddFile "hd0:stuff/thing"

@endnode

@node TBChgFileArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - ChgFileArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ChgFileArea <areaname>

Changes the current file area.  It is recommended that you use
@{"SelectFileArea" link TBSelectFileArea} instead of this, if possible.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ChgFileArea "General"

@endnode

@node TBChgMsgArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - ChgMsgArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ChgMsgArea <number>

Changes the current message area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ChgMsgArea "5"

@endnode

@node TBClearFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - ClearFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ClearFiles

Clears the list of files to send using the @{"SendFiles" link TBSendFiles} function.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ClearFiles

@endnode

@node TBClearMarkedFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - ClearMarkedFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ClearMarkedFiles

Clears the list of marked files.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ClearMarkedFiles

@endnode

@node TBClearMarkedMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - ClearMarkedMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ClearMarkedMsg

Clears the list of marked messages.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ClearMarkedMsg

@endnode

@node TBClearUser "TechnoBBS ARexx - ClearUser"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ClearUser

Clears all of the user information.  Returns the system to approximately
the same kind of state as before any user logged on.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ClearUser

@endnode

@node TBDisconnect "TechnoBBS ARexx - Disconnect"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Disconnect

Exits from TechnoBBS.  This is the command you should use before ending a
script.  A good idea would be to run your main ARexx script from a dos
script which calls another script that uses Disconnect (in case the main
script fails).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Disconnect

@endnode

@node TBDoneLogOn "TechnoBBS ARexx - DoneLogOn"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DoneLogOn

This should be called after the password has been verified.  It updates the
users call-related values (calls left, time left, last call, total calls).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DoneLogOn

@endnode

@node TBDownload "TechnoBBS ARexx - Download"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Download [<pattern>]

A high level file downloading command.  If an argument is specified, it
will be parsed as a filename-selection input for the command.  Wildcards
are valid in both the argument and in the input to the prompts.  If there
are files marked it moves them from the marked file list to the download
list.  If you specify "MARKEDONLY" instead of the pattern, only marked
files will be downloaded.

Starting with version 0.89, Download accepts numbers in addition to
patterns.  A string is parsed as numbers if it contains only decimal
digits, "-"s, " "s and ","s.  Commas or spaces can be used to separate
numbers, "-" indicates range.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Download "#?.lha"

@endnode

@node TBDumpASCII "TechnoBBS ARexx - DumpASCII"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DumpASCII <filename>

Dumps an ASCII file to the remote and the console.  As SendASCII except
that this just dumps the text, not checking when the users terminal screen
would be full.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DumpASCII "Text/Sometext.txt"

@endnode

@node TBEditMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - EditMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          EditMsg <number>

Edits the status bits of a message in the current message area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        EditMsg "5"

@endnode

@node TBFileRoot "TechnoBBS ARexx - FileRoot"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FileRoot

Changes the current file area to the root area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FileRoot

@endnode

@node TBFlushInput "TechnoBBS ARexx - FlushInput"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FlushInput

Waits for remote/console input to pause (usually this means waiting for the
devices' buffers to empty).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FlushInput

@endnode

@node TBKillMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - KillMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          KillMsg <number>

Kills a message in the current area.  Note that killing a message doesn't
mean removing it from the message file, since this would take far too much
time, KillMsg just marks the message as dead.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        KillMsg "29"

@endnode

@node TBSelectFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - SelectFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SelectFiles [<options>]

Allows the user to select files using the cursor keys for scanning the file
list.  The option string contains options each preceded by a '-' and
separated by spaces.

Options:        A - All files, all subdirectories
                E - All files in this area and its subdirectories
                H - Highlight file names instead of using a '>' to indicate
                    position (recommended)
                C - Show subdirectories and enable directory swicthing
                    (Note: turns off -E)
                P<pattern> - Only files matching pattern
                F<string> - Only files with <string> in name or comment
                D<date> - Only files since and including <date>
                        Date is either in AmigaDOS dd-mmm-yy format or as a
                        number representing days since 1-Jan-78.
                S<method> - Sort (Default: Newest to oldest)
                        N - Newest to oldest
                        O - Oldest to newest
                        A - Alphabetical
                        Z - Reverse alphabetical
                        <anything else> - None

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SelectFiles "-C -H -SA"

@endnode

@node TBListFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - ListFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ListFiles [<options>]

Lists files in current/all/sub areas depending on the options.  The option
string contains options each preceded by a '-' and separated by spaces.

Options:        A - All files, all subdirectories
                E - All files in this area and its subdirectories
                C - Continuous, no prompts
                B - Don't list subdirectories
                I - Ignore directories (list files mixed)
                N - No empty directories
                M - Show file numbers
                L - Show long descriptions
                G - Full area names (w/area path)
                O - C-style formatting string:
                        %n - filename
                        %s - size
                        %c - comment
                        %d - date
                        %t - time
                        %a - day
                        %p - protection
                P<pattern> - Only files matching <pattern>
                F<string> - Only files with <string> in name or comment
                D<date> - Only files since and including <date>
                        Date is either in AmigaDOS dd-mmm-yy format or as a
                        number representing days since 1-Jan-78.
                S<method> - Sort (Default: no sorting)
                        N - Newest to oldest
                        O - Oldest to newest
                        A - Alphabetical
                        Z - Reverse alphabetical

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ListFiles "-A -B -I -SA -P#?.(lha|lzh)"

@endnode

@node TBListMarkedFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - ListMarkedFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ListMarkedFiles

Produces a simple list of marked files.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ListMarkedFiles

@endnode

@node TBListMarkedMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - ListMarkedMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ListMarkedMsg

Produces a simple list of marked messages.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ListMarkedMsg

@endnode

@node TBListMessages "TechnoBBS ARexx - ListMessages"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ListMessages <start> <end>

Lists message headers in current area from <start> to <end>.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ListMessages "2 9"

@endnode

@node TBLoadUser "TechnoBBS ARexx - LoadUser"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LoadUser <name>

Loads a user to be the current user logged on to the BBS.  This function
only loads the user information and sets the terminal settings to those of
the user, you should also use @{"DoneLogOn" link TBDoneLogOn}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LoadUser "John Doe"

@endnode

@node TBLockCarrier "TechnoBBS ARexx - LockCarrier"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LockCarrier
                UnLockCarrier

Prevents TechnoBBS from disconnecting if the carrier is lost.  This is
useful if you are doing something that must not be interrupted, even if the
carrier is lost.  You should remember to UnLockCarrier after you are done
and skip any parts where you may have to prompt input from the user if
@{"CheckCarrier" link TBCheckCarrier} returns a carrier loss.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LockCarrier

@endnode

@node TBLogEntry "TechnoBBS ARexx - LogEntry"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogEntry <string>

Makes an entry into the nodes log.  The date and time of the entry are
automatically written before the specified string, and a linefeed after the
string, so you only need to specify the actual text.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogEntry "Disconnected node 4"

@endnode

@node TBMarkAnyFile "TechnoBBS ARexx - MarkAnyFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MarkAnyFile <filename>

Marks any file on any device.  You must specify a full path for the file,
since it's not searched for from the file areas.  The file is marked as a
free download.

If the filename begins with a %, the % is skipped and the file is deleted
after it is successfully sent.  (0.93+)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MarkAnyFile "SYS:stuff/somefile.lha"

@endnode

@node TBMarkFile "TechnoBBS ARexx - MarkFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MarkFile [<pattern>]

Marks files specified in the pattern.  If no pattern is specified, prompts
user for input.  Similar to @{"Download" link TBDownload}.  If the first
character in the option string is an '!', it will be skipped and MarkFile
won't output any info on the files matching the pattern.

Starting with version 0.89, MarkFile accepts numbers.  See @{"Download" link TBDownload} for
more specific information.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MarkFile "#?ami#?"

@endnode

@node TBMarkMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - MarkMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MarkMsg <area> <message>

Marks message number <message> in area number <area>.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MarkMsg "2 938"

@endnode

@node TBMoveMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - MoveMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MoveMsg <message> <area>

Moves message number <message> from the current area to area number <area>.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MoveMsg "28 9"

@endnode

@node TBPageSysOp "TechnoBBS ARexx - PageSysOp"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          PageSysOp

Tries to activate paging for the SysOp.  Informs the user that either the
page is activated, the page is already active or the SysOp is not
available.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        PageSysOp

@endnode

@node TBParentFileArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - ParentFileArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ParentFileArea

Changes the current file area to the parent of the current area, if it has
a parent.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ParentFileArea

@endnode

@node TBReadAllNew "TechnoBBS ARexx - ReadAllNew"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ReadAllNew

As @{"ReadNext" link TBReadNext} except that ReadAllNew scans all the areas.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ReadAllNew

@endnode

@node TBReadFrom "TechnoBBS ARexx - ReadFrom"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ReadFrom <message>

Starts @{"reading messages" link TBMsgRead} from <message>.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ReadFrom "34"

@endnode

@node TBReadMarked
TITLE "TechnoBBS ARexx - ReadMarked"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ReadMarked

@{"Reads the messages" link TBMsgRead} in the marked message list and
clears the marked message list.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ReadMarked

@endnode

@node TBReadNext "TechnoBBS ARexx - ReadNext"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ReadNext

Starts @{"reading messages" link TBMsgRead} in the current area from the first unread message
in the area.  If there are no new messages in the current area, moves on to
the next area.  Using ReadNext is the recommended way of reading messages
online.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ReadNext

@endnode

@node TBSaveUser "TechnoBBS ARexx - SaveUser"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SaveUser

Saves the data on the current user to disk.  Creates the user if there
isn't already an entry for the user.  If you have an unstable system, you
might want to call this after every action that might change the users data
(highread-pointers, filetransfer-stats, changes in access etc.).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SaveUser

@endnode

@node TBSelectFileArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - SelectFileArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SelectFileArea [<area>]

If a parameter is specified, changes the file area to the specified number,
if not, lists file areas available to the user and prompts the user to
select an area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SelectFileArea "5"

@endnode

@node TBSelectMsgArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - SelectMsgArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SelectMsgArea

Lists message areas available to the user and prompts them to select an
area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SelectMsgArea

@endnode

@node TBSendASCII "TechnoBBS ARexx - SendASCII"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SendASCII <filename>

Sends an ASCII file to the console and remote.  Prompts for "More?" each
time the number of lines configured for the users terminal get filled.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendASCII "Text/Garbage.txt"

@endnode

@node TBSendMenu "TechnoBBS ARexx - SendMenu"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SendMenu <filename>

Sends an ASCII file to the console and remote.  The differences between
this and @{"SendASCII" link TBSendASCII} are that SendMenu tries opening different variations of
the filename depending on the users character set and extension
configurations and aborts sending the text if any key is pressed (ie.
input is received) during the send.  Note that the input is not read by
this routine, so you will have it available for any routine you call after
SendMenu.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendMenu "Text/MainMenu"

@endnode

@node TBSendModem "TechnoBBS ARexx - SendModem"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SendModem <string>

Sends the string to the console and the remote, performing character set
conversion, ANSI-stripping (either only colors or all, depending on the
user's configuration) and color conversion (for the console) to the string.
Note that SendModem doesn't add any carriage returns or linefeeds to the
sent string.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "This is text"||CRLF

(For this example, CRLF should be defined as D2C(13)||D2C(10), like in the
example scripts provided)

@endnode

@node TBSendModemWD "TechnoBBS ARexx - SendModemWD"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SendModemWD <string>

Sends a string to the modem and the console.  Does NOT perform any
character set conversions, ANSI-stripping or color conversion.  This should
normally be used for sending commands to the modem (which is something you
normally wouldn't do directly) or producing delays using the '~' character.
SendModemWD doesn't prevent modem escaping (ie. sending +++ strings), so if
you want to change your modem settings, SendModemWD would be what you might
want to use.  (Such as turn DTR hangup off to enable you to turn off
TechnoBBS and your mailer so you could switch to a normal terminal program
or do something with your machine that can't have TechnoBBS on the
background and not disconnect)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModemWD "~~~+++~~~AT&D0^M~ATO^M"

@endnode

@node TBSetAccessPreset "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetAccessPreset"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetAccessPreset <filename>

Sets the current users access related values to those defined in the file.
The file is an ascii file containing 10 lines:

        Access level
        Free bytes (-1 for unlimited)
        Free files (-1 for unlimited)
        Byte ratio
        File ratio
        Time/Day (-1 for unlimited)
        Time/Call (-1 for unlimited)
        Calls/Day (-1 for unlimited)
        Max. Time Bank
        Mask

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetAccessPreset "BBS:User/Preset/Normal.acc"

@endnode

@node TBSetAreaMode "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetAreaMode"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetAreaMode <area> <bool>

Sets whether a user is "joined" to a message area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetAreaMode "2 1"

@endnode

@node TBSetAverageCps "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetAverageCps"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetAverageCps <cps>
                SetAverageCpsMultiplier <multiplier>

Sets the average cps for a user.  This probably shouldn't need to be used,
since it is calculated automatically.  The multiplier means the amount of
transfers the average is the average of, so the next transfers influence
will be calculated correctly: (newcps + (oldcps * multiplier)) / multiplier
+ 1.  You should probably set the multiplier to 1 if you modify the cps,
except if you want the users actual cps values to have minimal effect.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetAverageCps "1539"
                SetAverageCpsMultiplier "1"

@endnode

@node TBSetByteRatio "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetByteRatio"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetByteRatio <ratio>

Sets the byte ratio of the user.  Whenever the user uploads a file, their
bytes left is increased by the size of the file multiplied by the byte
ratio.  If the user has access to unlimited bytes, this should probably be
set to zero.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetByteRatio "4"

@endnode

@node SetBytesDownloaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetBytesDownloaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetBytesDownloaded <bytes>

Sets the bytes downloaded value of the user.  This doesn't affect anything
and probably isn't necessary to use, except if you want to manually add
bytes to this value for files the user has received via low-level routines
or external programs.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetBytesDownloaded "10000000"

@endnode

@node TBSetBytesLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetBytesLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetBytesLeft <bytes>

Sets the amount of bytes the user has left available for download.  A value
of -1 indicates unlimited bytes.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetBytesLeft "6000000"

@endnode

@node TBSetBytesUploaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetBytesUploaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetBytesUploaded <bytes>

Sets the bytes uploaded value of the user.  This doesn't affect anything
and probably isn't necessary to use, except if you want to manually add
bytes to this value for files that have been received from the user with
low-level routines or external programs.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetBytesUploaded "2000000"

@endnode

@node TBSetCallsDay "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetCallsDay"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetCallsDay <calls>

Sets the number of calls a user is allowed per day.  -1 indicates unlimited
calls.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetCallsDay "3"

@endnode

@node TBSetCallsLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetCallsLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetCallsLeft <calls>

Sets the number of calls the user has left today (ie. the day indicated by
the users lastcall-value).  -1 indicates unlimited calls.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetCallsLeft "1"

@endnode

@node TBSetFileRatio "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetFileRatio"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetFileRatio <ratio>

Sets the file ratio of the user.  Whenever the user uploads a file, their
files left is increased by the file ratio.  If the user has access to
unlimited files, this should probably be set to zero.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetFileRatio "3"

@endnode

@node TBSetFilesDownloaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetFilesDownloaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetFilesDownloaded <files>

Sets the files downloaded value of the user.  This doesn't affect anything
and probably isn't necessary to use, except if you want to manually add
files to this value for files the user has received via low-level routines
or external programs.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetFilesDownloaded "3400"

@endnode

@node TBSetFilesLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetFilesLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetFilesLeft <files>

Sets the number of files the user has left available for download.  A value
of -1 indicates unlimited files.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetFilesLeft "500"

@endnode

@node TBSetFilesUploaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetFilesUploaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetFilesUploaded <files>

Sets the files uploaded value of the user.  This doesn't affect anything
and probably isn't necessary to use, except if you want to manually add
files to this value for files that have been received from the user with
low-level routines or external programs.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetFilesUploaded "20"

@endnode

@node TBSetHighRead "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetHighRead"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetHighRead <area> <message>

Sets the users highread value for a message area.  The value normally is
used to indicate the number of the last message that the user has read in
the area.  Reading new messages is started from the next message after the
one indicated by a users highread.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetHighRead "4 5874"

@endnode

@node TBSetMask "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetMask"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetMask <mask value>

Sets the users mask value.  This value is used for checking if the user has
access to some function.  If an "and" operation between the mask and the
mask required for the function results in a number equal to the mask
required for the function, the user has access to this function.  A value
of -1 (or 4294967295 or 0xffffffff) will give the user access to any masked
functions.  A value of 0 will not allow the user to use any function with a
mask value other than 0.  Since the mask is based on "bits", it is probably
easier to think of these in hex (or binary).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetMask "0"

@endnode

@node TBSetMaxTimeBank "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetMaxTimeBank"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetMaxTimeBank <minutes>

Sets the maximum time allowed for the user to store in their time bank.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetMaxTimeBank "1000"

See also:       @{"SetTimeBank" link TBSetTimeBank}

@endnode

@node TBSetMessages "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetMessages"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetMessages <messages>

Sets the messages written value of the user.  This doesn't affect anything,
so you'll probably never want to use this.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetMessages "104"

@endnode

@node TBSetPassword "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetPassword"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetPassword <password>

Sets the password of the current user.  The password can be any
ASCII-string.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetPassword "5m06dnjr3yj"

@endnode

@node TBSetSimpleTerm "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetSimpleTerm"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetSimpleTerm <bool>

Sets the users simple ANSI-terminal flag on or off.  Having the simple
terminal value set will prevent TechnoBBS for using the insert/delete
line ANSI-codes (^[[L and ^[[M) in the @{"split-screen chat" link TBChat} or the
@{"message editor" link TBMsgEditor}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetSimpleTerm "1"

@endnode

@node TBSetSlowTerm "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetSlowTerm"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetSlowTerm <bool>

Sets the users slow ANSI-terminal flag on or off (not actually meaning that
the terminal would be slow, but the baud-rate of the connection).  Having
this set will currently only cause the @{"split-screen chat" link TBChat} "screens" to be
cleared using insert/delete lines instead of clearing the lines one at a
time.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetSimpleTerm "0"

@endnode

@node TBSetStatus "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetStatus"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetStatus <string>

Sets the status of the node.  The string should be a description of what
the user is doing.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetStatus "Main menu"

@endnode

@node TBSetStripAll "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetStripAll"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetStripAll <bool>

Sets the users ANSI-code stripping flag on or off.  If set to true, all
ANSI-codes will be stripped from anything sent to this user.  Having this
set will also disable the @{"message editor" link TBMsgEditor} and cause a simpler chat to be
used instead of the @{"split-screen chat" link TBChat}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetStripAll "1"

@endnode

@node TBSetStripCols "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetStripCols"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetStripCols <bool>

Sets the user ANSI-color stripping flag on or off.  If set to true, all
color-related ANSI-codes (ones ending in 'm') to be stripped from anything
sent to this user.  This is useful if the user is using a screen with less
than 8 colors or just doesn't like ANSI-color.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetStripCols "1"

@endnode

@node TBSetTerminalLines "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetTerminalLines"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetTerminalLines <lines>

Sets the number of lines the user's terminal has.  This value is used to
calculate when a "More?"-prompt should be displayed and also to restrict
the size of the @{"split-screen chat" link TBChat} and the @{"message editor link TBMsgEditor}.

@endnode

@node TBSetTimeBank "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetTimeBank"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetTimeBank <minutes>

Sets the number of minutes a user has in their time bank.

NOTE:  The time bank of a user is used for nothing by TechnoBBS, if you
wish to use them, you just have to have support in your script.  In the
future, this may be used by TechnoBBS itself (eg. if a user is transferring
a file or in the message editor when their time runs out, the system will
switch to using the time in the time bank automatically).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetTimeBank "80"

@endnode

@node TBSetTimeCall "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetTimeCall"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetTimeCall <minutes>

Sets the amount of time a user is allowed to use during one call.  -1
indicates unlimited time.  If this is set to a higher value than the user
has left that day or -1, the time left of the user when logging on will be
set to what the user has left.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetTimeCall "40"

@endnode

@node TBSetTimeDay "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetTimeDay"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetTimeDay <minutes>

Sets the amount of time a user has during one day.  -1 indicates unlimited
time.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetTimeDay "60"

@endnode

@node TBSetTimeLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetTimeLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetTimeLeft <minutes>

Sets the amount of time the user has during this session.  -1 indicates
unlimited time.  This is not to be confused with @{"SetUserTimeLeft" link
TBSetUserTimeLeft}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetTimeLeft "120"

@endnode

@node TBSetTotalCalls "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetTotalCalls"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetTotalCalls <calls>

Sets the users total calls value.  This doesn't affect anything and you
probably won't have any reason to use this call.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetTotalCalls "78"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserAccess "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserAccess"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserAccess <value>

Sets the access level of a user.  This number is compared to the access
requirement for certain functions to see if the user has access to that
function.  If this value is greater than or equal to the required access
leve, the user is allowed to use the function.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserAccess "100"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserCharSet "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserCharSet <name>

Sets the character set to convert from/to for input/output to this user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserCharSet "IBM"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserExtension "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserExtension"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserExtension <string>

Sets the extension of a user.  The extension is a string which will be
appended to the filename given to @{"SendMenu" link TBSendMenu}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserExtension ".Txt"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserLanguage "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserLanguage"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserLanguage <name>

Sets the language to user for this user.  From version 0.84 (17-Dec-93)
this attempts to load a language file from String/<name> which contains the
system strings separated by ctrl-a characters (ascii 1).

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserLanguage "suomi"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserName "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserName <name>

Sets the name of the current user.  This routine does not modify anything
in the name you give it, any string will become the user's name.  If you
wish to check the name for validity (no strange characters), you'll have to
have your script to the check.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserName "John Doe"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserProtocol "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserProtocol"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserProtocol <name>

Sets the protocol to use for the users file transfers.  The protocol name
should the same as you have configured using the @{"Protocol" link TBProtocol} keyword.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserProtocol "ZModem"

@endnode

@node TBSetUserTimeLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserTimeLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SetUserTimeLeft <minutes>

Sets the amount of time the user has left today.  Doesn't affect the time
left during the current session.  Shouldn't be confused with @{"SetTimeLeft" link TBSetTimeLeft}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SetUserTimeLeft "50"

@endnode

@node TBShowMessage "TechnoBBS ARexx - ShowMessage"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ShowMessage <text>

Shows some text to the user, followed by a "Press a key.."-prompt.  This
should usually be used by anything running asynchronously with your main
script.  The @{"example scripts" link ExampleScripts} use it for node messages and @{"TechQWK" link TechQWK} uses it
to inform the user that it is done, if run asynchronously.  ShowMessage
returns immediately, even if there isn't a possibility to show the message
yet (the user is chatting, transferring files etc..).  The message will be
displayed as soon as possible.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ShowMessage "Nobody knows where this came from"

@endnode

@node TBUpdateFileList "TechnoBBS ARexx - UpdateFileList"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UpdateFileList

Causes TechnoBBS to tell TechCon to update the global list of files.  The
file-directories are re-read and a new files.dat is created.  This is
useful if you want to have an 'add file' command on the BBS.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UpdateFileList

@endnode

@node TBUpload "TechnoBBS ARexx - Upload"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Upload

For now, Upload starts receiving immediately (except if the user doesn't
have upload access in the current area or there isn't enough space for
uploads) and if any files are received, checks them and asks for
descriptions.  After this it tells TechCon to update the global list of
files.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Upload

@endnode

@node TBWriteMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - WriteMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          WriteMsg [<options>]

Enables the user to write a message into the current message area.
WriteMsg will ask for the net address (only if in the netmail area), the
user to write the message to (if not specified as an option) and the
subject (if not specified as an option).  After this the @{"message editor" link TBMsgEditor}
is activated.  Two options are supported:  -t<to user> and -s<subject>.  -s
must always be the last option if included.  A space followed by a '-' (the
next option) or end of string indicates the ending of the -t option.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        WriteMsg "-tSysOp -sFeedback"

@endnode

@node TBAskInput "TechnoBBS ARexx - AskInput"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}  string = AskInput(<node, <prompt>, <default>, <max.  length>
                          [, "NUMERIC" ] [, "SECURE" ])

Asks the user for string input.  Provides editing using [shift] cursor
left/right, backspace and del and a command line history using [shift]
cursor up/down.  Ctrl+X clears the string being displayed.  If you specify
a default string, it is sent to the user after the prompt and can be
edited.  If the "NUMERIC" option is specified, only numbers will be
accepted in the string.  If the "SECURE" option is used, a '-' will be sent
to the console and remote in place of each character and the string entered
will not be stored in the command line history buffer.  The function
returns the string entered.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UserName = AskInput(1, "Enter username: ", "", 36)

@endnode

@node TBCheckCarrier "TechnoBBS ARexx - CheckCarrier"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = CheckCarrier(<node>)

Returns the status of the serial DCD for the node.  Unless the @{"IgnoreDCD" link TBIgnoreDCD}
option is set or @{"LockCarrier" link TBLockCarrier} has been used, TechnoBBS will exit on carrier
loss and this function isn't necessary to use.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if CheckCarrier(1) = 0 then exit 0

@endnode

@node TBCheckPassword "TechnoBBS ARexx - CheckPassword"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = CheckPassword(<node>, <string>)

Returns true if the string matches the password of the user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if CheckPassword(1, Password) then SendModem "Correct!"

@endnode

@node TBGetAreaMode "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetAreaMode"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = GetAreaMode(<node>, <message area>)

Returns a boolean value indicating whether the user has a message area
selected.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if GetAreaMode(1, 6) = 1 then ChgMsgArea 6

@endnode

@node TBGetAverageCps "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetAverageCps"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          cps = GetAverageCps(<node>)
                mult = GetAverageCpsMultiplier(<node>)

These functions return the users average cps and the number of times that
have been used to calculate it.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Your average cps is "||GetAverageCps(1)

See also:       @{"SetAverageCps" link TBSetAverageCps}

@endnode

@node TBGetByteRatio "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetByteRatio"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ratio = GetByteRatio(<node>)

Returns the users byte ratio.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have a byte-ratio of 1:"||GetByteRatio(1)

See also:       @{"SetByteRatio" link TBSetByteRatio}

@endnode

@node TBGetBytesDownloaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetBytesDownloaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bytes = GetBytesDownloaded(<node>)

Returns the number of bytes the user has downloaded.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have downloaded "||GetBytesDownloaded(1)||" bytes"

@endnode

@node TBGetBytesLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetBytesLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bytes = GetBytesLeft(<node>)

Returns the number of bytes the user has left available for download.  -1
indicates unlimited bytes.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        bytes = GetBytesLeft(1)
                if bytes < 0 then bytes = "unlimited"
                SendModem "You have "||bytes||" available for downloading"

@endnode

@node TBGetBytesUploaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetBytesUploaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bytes = GetBytesUploaded

Returns the number of bytes the user has uploaded.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have uploaded "||GetBytesUploaded(1)||" bytes"

@endnode

@node TBGetCallsDay "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetCallsDay"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          calls = GetCallsDay(<node>)

Returns the number of calls the user is allowed a day.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You are allowed "||GetCallsDay(1)||" calls/day"

@endnode

@node TBGetCallsLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetCallsLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          calls = GetCallsLeft(<node>)

Returns the number of calls the user has left today.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have "||GetCallsLeft(1)||" calls left today"

@endnode

@node TBGetDateVal "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetDateVal"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          days = GetDateVal(<node>)

Returns the number of days since 1-Jan-78.  This should be used for the
date value in @{"ListFiles" link TBListFiles".

@{b}Example:@{ub}        call SetUserMisc 1, "LASTFSCAN", GetDateVal(1)

@endnode

@node TBGetFileArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetFileArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          areaname = GetFileArea(<node>)

Returns the name of the current file area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "File area: "||GetFileArea(1)

@endnode

@node TBGetFilePath "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetFilePath"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          fullname = GetFilePath(<node>, <pattern>)

Returns the full path and name of the first file found in the file base
that matches the given pattern.  Usually you will probably want to specify
the name of a file as the pattern.

Starting with version 0.89, GetFilePath also accepts numbers.  See @{"Download" link TBDownload}
for more specific information.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        file = GetFilePath(1, "archive.lha")

@endnode

@node TBGetFileRatio "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetFileRatio"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ratio = GetFileRatio(<node>)

Returns the users file ratio.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have a file ratio of 1:"||GetFileRatio(1)

See also:       @{"SetFileRatio" link TBSetFileRatio}

@endnode

@node TBGetFilesDownloaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetFilesDownloaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          files = GetFilesDownloaded(<node>)

Returns the number of files the user has downloaded.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have downloaded "||GetFilesDownloaded(1)||" files"

@endnode

@node TBGetFilesLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetFilesLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          files = GetFilesLeft(<node>)

Returns the number of files the user has left available for download.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        files = GetFilesLeft(1)
                if files < 0 then files = "unlimited"
                SendModem "You have "||files||" available for downloading"

@endnode

@node TBGetFilesUploaded "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetFilesUploaded"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          files = GetFilesUploaded(<node>)

Returns the number of files the user has uploaded.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have uploaded "||GetFilesUploaded(1)||" files"

@endnode

@node TBGetHighRead "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetHighRead"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          highread = GetHighRead(<node>, <message area>)

Returns the number of the last message read in a message area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem GetHighRead(1, 4)||"/"||GetHighMsg(1, 4)

@endnode

@node TBGetHighMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetHighMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          highmsg = GetHighMsg(<node>, <message area>)

Returns the highest message number in a message area.  If there are no
messages in the area, this is a zero.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem GetHighRead(1, 4)||"/"||GetHighMsg(1, 4)

@endnode

@node TBGetHotkey "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetHotkey"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          key = GetHotkey(<node>, <prompt>)

Waits until the user presses a key and returns the key pressed.  Doesn't
echo the key pressed.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        call GetHotkey 1, "Press a key.."

@endnode

@node TBGetLowMsg "TechnoBBS ARexx = GetLowMsg"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          lowmsg = GetLowMsg(<node>, <message area>)

Returns the number of the first message in a message area.  If there are no
messages in the area, this is a zero.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        msgs = GetHighMsg(1, 2) - GetLowMsg(1, 2) + 1

@endnode

@node TBGetMask "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetMask"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          mask = GetMask(<node>)

Returns the mask of the user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        mask = GetMask(1)

See also:       @{"SetMask" link TBSetMask}

@endnode

@node TBGetMaxTimeBank "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetMaxTimeBank"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          maxtime = GetMaxTimeBank(<node>)

Gets the maximum value of time a user can have in their time bank.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Maximum: "||GetMaxTimeBank(1)" minutes"

See also:       @{"SetTimeBank" link TBSetTimeBank}

@endnode

@node TBGetMessages "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetMessages"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          messages = GetMessages(<node>)

Returns the number of messages a user has written.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have written "||GetMessages(1)||" messages"

@endnode

@node TBGetMsgArea "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetMsgArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          areanum = GetMsgArea(<node>)

Returns the number of the current message area of the user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Current area: "||GetMsgArea(1)

@endnode

@node TBGetMsgAreaName "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetMsgAreaName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          area = GetMsgAreaName(<node>, <message area>)

Returns the name of a message area.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Current area: "||GetMsgAreaName(1, GetMsgArea(1))

@endnode

@node TBGetPassword "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetPassword"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          password = GetPassword(<node>)

Returns the password of the user.  It doesn't make any sense to use this
starting with version 0.87, since the password is in encrypted form and
can't be decrypted.  In any situation other than after changing the
password this will return an encrypted password.  You can test whether
whatever this returns is encrypted or not, since encrypted passwords always
begin with a ctrl-a (byte value 1).

@{b}See also:@{ub}       @{"CheckPassword" link TBCheckPassword}

@endnode

@node TBGetSimpleTerm "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetSimpleTerm"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = GetSimpleTerm(<node>)

Returns a boolean value indicating whether the user is using a simple
terminal.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if GetSimpleTerm(1) = 1 then SendModem "Simple terminal"

See also:       @{"SetSimpleTerm" link TBSetSimpleTerm}

@endnode

@node TBGetSlowTerm "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetSlowTerm"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = GetSlowTerm(<node>)

Returns a boolean value indicating whether the user is using a slow
terminal.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if GetSlowTerm(1) = 1 then SendModem "Slow terminal"

See also:       @{"SetSlowTerm" link TBSetSlowTerm}

@endnode

@node TBGetStripAll "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetStripAll"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = GetStripAll(<node>)

Returns a boolean value indicating whether the user has ANSI-stripping
turned on.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if GetStripAll(1) = 1 then SendModem "Non-ANSI terminal"

See also:       @{"SetStripAll" link TBSetStripAll}

@endnode

@node TBGetStripCols "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetStripCols"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = GetStripCols(<node>)

Returns a boolean value indicating whether the user has ANSI-color
stripping turned on.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if GetStripCols(1) =  1 then SendModem "No color"

See also:       @{"SetStripCols" link TBSetStripCols}

@endnode

@node TBGetTerminalLines "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetTerminalLines"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          lines = GetTerminalLines(<node>)

Returns the number of lines the user has on their terminal.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem GetTerminalLines(1)||" lines"

See also:       @{"SetTerminalLines" link TBSetTerminalLines}

@endnode

@node TBGetTimeBank "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetTimeBank"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          time = GetTimeBank(<node>)

Returns the amount of time a user has in their time bank.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "TimeBank: "||GetTimeBank(1)||" minutes"

See also:       @{"SetTimeBank" link TBSetTimeBank}

@endnode

@node TBGetTimeCall "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetTimeCall"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          minutes = GetTimeCall(<node>)

Returns the amount of time the user is allowed during a call.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You are allowed "||GetTimeCall(1)||" minutes/call"

See also:       @{"SetTimeCall" link TBSetTimeCall}

@endnode

@node TBGetTimeDay "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetTimeDay"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          minutes = GetTimeDay(<node>)

Returns the amount of time the user has during one day.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You are allower "||GetTimeDay(1)||" minutes/day"

See also:       @{"SetTimeDay" link TBSetTimeDay}

@endnode

@node TBGetTimeLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetTimeLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          minutes = GetTimeLeft(<node>)

Returns the amount of time left during this call.  A '-' will be returned
for unlimited time.  This should not be confused with @{"GetUserTimeLeft" link TBGetUserTimeLeft}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Time left: "||GetTimeLeft(<node>)

@endnode

@node TBGetTotalCalls "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetTotalCalls"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          calls = GetTotalCalls(<node>)

Returns the total number of calls the user has made.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You have called "||GetTotalCalls(1)||" times"

@endnode

@node TBGetUserAccess "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserAccess"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          access = GetUserAccess(<node>)

Returns the access level of the user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Your access: "||GetUserAccess(1)

See also:       @{"SetUserAccess" link TBSetUserAccess}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserCharSet "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          charset = GetUserCharSet(<node>)

Returns the name of the character set the user is using.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Using the "||GetUserCharSet(1)||" character set"

See also:       @{"SetUserCharSet" link TBSetUserCharSet}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserExtension "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserExtension"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          extension = GetUserExtension(<node>)

Returns the users extension.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendASCII "Text/Something"||GetUserExtension(1)

See also:       @{"SetUserExtension" link TBSetUserExtension}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserLanguage "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserLanguage"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          language = GetUserLanguage(<node>)

Returns the language of the user.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Language: "||GetUserLanguage(1)

See also:       @{"SetUserLanguage" link TBSetUserLanguage}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserMisc "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserMisc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          misc = GetUserMisc(<node>, <ID>)

Searches the user's miscallaneous setting list for the ID.  If the ID is
found, the string associated with it is returned.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Your live on "||GetUserMisc(1, "STREET")

See also:       @{"SetUserMisc" link TBSetUserMisc}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserName "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          name = GetUserName(<node>)

Returns the name of the user currently logged on, or an empty string if no
user is logged on.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "You are: "||GetUserName(<node>)

See also:       @{"SetUserName" link TBSetUserName}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserPath "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserPath"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          path = GetUserPath(<node>, <username>)

Returns the path of a user's directory.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        path = GetUserPath(1, GetUserName(1))

@endnode

@node TBGetUserProtocol "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserProtocol"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          protocol = GetUserProtocol(<node>)

Returns the name of the protocol the user has selected.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem "Protocol: "||GetUserProtocol(1)

See also:       @{"SetUserProtocol" link TBSetUserProtocol}

@endnode

@node TBGetUserTimeLeft "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetUserTimeLeft"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          minutes = GetUserTimeLeft(<node>)

Returns the amount of time the user has left today.  This shouldn't be
confused with @{"GetTimeLeft" link TBGetTimeLeft}.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendModem GetUserTimeLeft(1)||" minutes left today"

See also:       @{"SetUserTimeLeft" link TBSetUserTimeLeft}

@endnode

@node TBGetYesNo "TechnoBBS ARexx - GetYesNo"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = GetYesNo(<node>, <prompt>, <default>)

Prompts the user for a Y/N answer.  The default indicates what will be
displayed highlighted and selected if the user presses return.  Note that
this function only sends a carriage return and no line feed when exiting.
(This is so prompts such as "More? " could written over)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if GetYesNo(1, "Do something? ", 0) then ...

@endnode

@node TBHasMsgAcc "TechnoBBS ARexx - HasMsgAcc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = HasMsgAcc(<node>, <area>)

Returns true if the user has access to message area number <area>.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if HasMsgAcc(1, 4) then ...

@endnode

@node TBMessageCheck "TechnoBBS ARexx - MessageCheck"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = MessageCheck(<node>)

Checks if there are messages addressed to the user.  Marks any messages
that are waiting.  Returns true if messages were found.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if MessageCheck(1) then ReadMarked

@endnode

@node TBReceiveFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - ReceiveFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = ReceiveFiles(<node> [, <filename>])

This is a low-level file receiving routine.  Returns success.  Received
files are always placed in the user's directory.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if ReceiveFiles(1) = 0 then SendModem "Tranfer failed"

@endnode

@node TBSearchMessages "TechnoBBS ARexx - SearchMessages"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          found = SearchMessages(<node>, <start>, <end>, <string>)

Searches the messages in the current area ranging from <start> to <end> for
<string>.  Returns a string containing the numbers of the messages the
string was found in separated by spaces.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        call SearchMessages 1, 1, GetHighMsg(1, 4), "Amiga"

@endnode

@node TBSendFiles "TechnoBBS ARexx - SendFiles"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          bool = SendFiles(<node>, [, <filename>])

This is a low-level file sending routine.  Returns success.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        if SendFiles(1) = 0 then SendModem "Transfer failed"

See also:       @{"ClearFiles" link TBClearFiles} @{"AddFile" link TBAddFile}

@endnode

@node TBSetUserMisc "TechnoBBS ARexx - SetUserMisc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          call SetUserMisc <node>, <ID>, <string>

Sets a value in the miscallaneous setting list of the user.  If an entry
with the ID already exists, the value of the setting is updated.

The miscallaneous settings can be used for anything.  If there is an option
that TechnoBBS doesn't have available, you might want to use these.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        call SetUserMisc 1, "LASTFSCAN", GetDateVal(1)

@endnode

@node TechnoBBSWin "TechnoBBS - Interface"

        The TechnoBBS window:

The titlebar of the window indicates the TechnoBBS version being used and
the node number.  The close gadget can be used to close the window (this
will not quit the node -- you can get the window back using TechCon).
There are also system gadgets for depth arrangement, zoom and window
sizing (sizing the window down too small vertically may result in you not
being able to use the size-gadget any further).

        The menus:

Most of the operations the SysOp can perform are contained in the menus:

        @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub}

@{b}About..@{ub} displays an information requester.

@{b}Exit@{ub} exits the node.

        @{b}Window:@{ub}

@{b}Close Window@{ub} closes the window, like the close-gadget.

@{b}Iconify@{ub} zips the window.

        @{b}User:@{ub}

@{b}Edit@{ub} edits the user currently logged on.

@{b}Clear@{ub} clears the user information for the node.

@{b}Re-Load@{ub} re-loads the data of the current user.  This should be
used after editing the user for the changes to take effect.

@{b}Load New@{ub} loads a different user than the one logged on currently.
The menu item brings up an asl filerequester, but you should use the
requester to type in the name of the user to load, not to select a file.

@{b}Save@{ub} saves the information of the user.

@{b}Free time@{ub} when checked, this prevents the time left on the node
from being decreased.

@{b}Free transfer@{ub} when checked, the user can download files without
them affecting the bytes or files left.

        @{b}Command:@{ub}

@{b}Chat@{ub} activates a @{"chat" link TBChat} mode with the user currently logged on.

@{b}Send file@{ub} sends a file to the user using the protocol the user has
selected for use.  The file is selected using an asl filerequester.

@{b}Send ASCII@{ub} sends an ASCII file to the console and remote.  THe
file is selected using an asl filerequester.

@{b}Dump ASCII@{ub} like Send ASCII, except that no "More?"-prompts are
presented.

@{b}Receive file@{ub} turns on the receive mode of the protocol the user
has selected for use.  Any files received are placed in the user's
directory.

        @{b}Special:@{ub}

@{b}Serial enable@{ub} enables/disables remote (serial) I/O.  Ignored by
the local node.

@{b}Page enable@{ub} toggles SysOp availability.

@{b}ARexx enable@{ub} enables/disables the processing of ARexx commands.

@{b}Flush buffers@{ub} empties the console and remote I/O buffers.

@{b}Update filelist@{ub} updates the global list of files.

@{b}Paste clipboard@{ub} pastes the contents of the clipboard into the
buffer of the message editor or chat.  Ignored otherwise.

@{b}Save message@{ub} is only enabled after reading a message.  Saves the
contents of the message to a file (appending it).  The file is selected
using an asl filerequester.

        @{b}Chat:@{ub} (only enabled when in chat)

@{b}Enable user quit@{ub} enables/disables the users quit and beep control.

@{b}Write on user@{ub} jumps to and from the users half of the screen (in
the split screen chat).

@{b}Save SBuffer@{ub} saves the SysOp's chat buffer (in the split screen
chat) to a file (appending it).  The file is selected using an asl
filerequester.

@{b}Save UBuffer@{ub} saves the user's chat buffer (in the split screen
chat) to a file (appending it).  The file is selected using an asl
filerequester.

@endnode

@node TBChat "TechnoBBS - Chat"

In addition to the menu functions available to the SysOp described in the
section about the @{"TechnoBBS interface" link TechnoBBSWin} the chat mode in TechnoBBS provides
the following commands available to both the SysOp and the user:

 ^Q - Quit

Exits the chat.

 ^R - Redraw

Redraws the chat screen (only in the split screen chat).

 ^L - Clear

Clears the section of the screen this is typed in (only in the split screen
chat).

        @{b}Other keys:@{ub}

@{b}Cursor up@{ub} moves the cursor upwards.  Only functional in the split
screen chat.

@{b}Cursor down@{ub} moves the cursor downwards.  Only functional in the
split screen chat.

@{b}Cursor left@{ub} moves the cursor to the left.  Only functional in the
split screen chat.

@{b}Cursor right@{ub} moves the cursor to the right.  Only functional in
the split screen chat.

@{b}Shift + Cursor up@{ub} moves the cursor to the top of the currently visible area
or up one page if already at the top of the visible area.  Only functional
in the split screen chat.

@{b}Shift + Cursor down@{ub} moves the cursor to the bottom of the currently visible
area or down one page if already at the bottom of the visible area.  Only
functional in the split screen chat.

@{b}Shift + Cursor left@{ub} moves the cursor to the beginning of the current line.
Only functional in the split screen chat.

@{b}Shift + Cursor right@{ub} moves the cursor to the end of the current line.
Only functional in the split screen chat.

@{b}Backspace@{ub} deletes the character left of the cursor and moves the cursor to
the left.

@{b}Del@{ub} deletes the character under the cursor and shifts the rest of the line
to the left.  Only functional in the split screen chat.  New: The next line
will be added to the end of the current one if possible.

@{b}Return/Enter@{ub} inserts a new line into the text to where the cursor is
currently located.

@{b}A key with a character equivalent@{ub} inserts the character into the text where
the cursor is currently located.

@endnode

@node TBMsgEditor "TechnoBBS - Message Editor"

The default full screen editor is built in to the TechnoBBS executable, so
it is your only choice for now.  It should be adequate for most uses,
though.

The display of the editor should be self-explanatory, the commands are as
follows:  (the '^'-character means pressing the ctrl key simultaneously
with the key following the '^')

 ^Z - Save & Quit

Saves the message and quits the editor.

 ^C - Abort message

Quits the editor without saving the message.  Asks for verification.

 ^A - Help

Displays a list of commands in the editor.

 ^R - Redraw

Re-draws the message editor screen.

 ^X - Clear message

Clears the message text.  Asks for verification.

 ^Q - Quote

If this message is a reply to another message, this inserts the body of the
message this message is a reply to in the editor buffer (with the initials
of the original writer prefixed to each line).

 ^K - Kill line

Kills the line the cursor is currently on.

 ^L - Insert killed line

Inserts the contents of the last killed line to where the cursor is.

 ^Y - Kill to EOL

Kills from the cursor position to the end of the current line.

 ^U - Upload file to attach

Starts receiving with the protocol selected for the current user.  The file
that is received is marked as the messages file-attach.  The actual file
remains in the user's directory and can be downloaded by anyone who can
read the message.

 ^T - Change recipient

Edits the name of the recipient of the message.

 ^S - Change subject

Edits the subject of the message.

 ^P - Change private status

Asks whether the message should be sent as a private message or not.

 ^F - Change destination address

Edits the destination address of the message.  The destination field is
ignored in all other messages except ones in a netmail-area.

 ^B - Change area

Changes the area the message is going to.

        @{b}Other keys:@{ub}

@{b}Cursor up@{ub} moves the cursor upwards.

@{b}Cursor down@{ub} moves the cursor downwards.

@{b}Cursor left@{ub} moves the cursor to the left.

@{b}Cursor right@{ub} moves the cursor to the right.

@{b}Shift + Cursor up@{ub} moves the cursor to the top of the currently visible area
or up one page if already at the top of the visible area.

@{b}Shift + Cursor down@{ub} moves the cursor to the bottom of the currently visible
area or down one page if already at the bottom of the visible area.

@{b}Shift + Cursor left@{ub} moves the cursor to the beginning of the current line.

@{b}Shift + Cursor right@{ub} moves the cursor to the end of the current line.

@{b}Backspace@{ub} deletes the character left of the cursor and moves the cursor to
the left.

@{b}Del@{ub} deletes the character under the cursor and shifts the rest of the line
to the left.

@{b}Return/Enter@{ub} inserts a new line into the text to where the cursor is
currently located.

@{b}A key with a character equivalent@{ub} inserts the character into the text where
the cursor is currently located.

@endnode

@node TBMsgRead "TechnoBBS - Reading messages"

When reading messages the first part of a message that is displayed is its
header information:

@{b}Date:@{ub} <date>

The date field shows the date and time when the message was written.

@{b}From:@{ub} <name>

The from field shows who the message was written by.

@{b}To:@{ub} <name>

The to field shows who the message was written to.

@{b}Subject:@{ub} <string>

The subject field shows the subject description of the message.

  <area name>: <msg. number>/<highest message in area> [<additional>]

The additional stuff will only be displayed if they apply to the message.
The possible additional fields that may be displayed are:

@{b}O@{ub}(<original message>)

Indicates the number of the message that this message is a reply to.  When
this field is displayed, 'O' can be used to jump to the original message.

@{b}F@{ub}(<first reply>)

Indicates the number of the first reply to this message.  When this this
field is displayed, 'F' can be used to jump to the first reply.

@{b}-@{ub}(<previous reply>)

Indicates the number of the previous message that is a reply to the same
original message as this one.  When this field is displayed, '-' can be
used to jump to the previous reply.

@{b}+@{ub}(<next reply>)

Indicates the number of the next messasge that is a reply to the same
original message as this one.  When this field is displayed, '+' can be
used to jump to the next reply.

@{b}D@{ub}(<name of attached file>)

Indicates the name of the file attached to this message.  When this field
is displayed, 'D' can be used to download the attached file.

@{b}P@{ub}

Indicates that the message is private.

@{b}R@{ub}

Indicates that the message has been received.

@{b}(K)ill (E)dit@{ub}

This field is shown only if the user has access to read private messages to
others, kill messages and edit message bits in this area.  When this field
is displayed, 'K' can be used to kill the current message and 'E' can be
used to edit the bits of the current message.

If the length of these fields would go off the right edge of the screen,
they will be cut.

The message body (the actual text content of the message) is displayed
beneath this information, in several screens separated by "More?"-prompts
if necessary.

After the entire message body has been displayed, a command prompt will be
presented.  The commands (in addition to the ones indicated by the special
additional information) are:

@{b}[N]ext@{ub} Continues reading to the next available message.

@{b}(A)gain@{ub} Displays the message text of the current message again.

@{b}(P)revious@{ub} Jumps back to the previous message.

@{b}(M)ark@{ub} Asks for a message number to mark.

@{b}(R)eply@{ub} Writes a reply to this message using the @{"message editor" link TBMsgEditor}.

@{b}(J)ump@{ub} Asks for a message number to jump to.

@{b}(Q)uit@{ub} Stops reading messages.

@endnode

@node TechMail "TechMail"

@{b}@{i}TechMail @{ub}@{ui}is the FidoNet "tosser" of the TechnoBBS system, ie. the program
that handles inbound/outbound mail in packets and bundles.  It is capable
of doing this asynchronously, since it uses the message routines in TechCon
for access to the message base.

You will probably want to either configure TechCon to run TechMail
automatically at least before and after each time a remote system is called
or you might want to have TechMail run each time somebody logs off or every
hour or even every minute (if you want someone that might poll messages any
time to get as much of the new messages as possible).

TechMail requires TechCon to be running.

To run TechMail:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechMail [<configuration file>]

When run, TechMail will search for either the specified configuration file
or 'BBS:Cfg/TechMail.Cfg' if not specified.  It will do a combination of
@{"importing" link Import}, @{"exporting" link Export} and @{"tossing" link Toss} depending on the configuration.

        @{"  TechMail - Configuration  " link TechMailCfg}

@endnode

@node Import "Import"

Importing is the process of reading messages from FidoNet mail packets that
have been received from other BBS's and writing them to the BBS's message
areas.

@endnode

@node Export "Export"

Exporting is the process of reading messages from the BBS's message areas
and packing them into FidoNet mail packets and bundles, which will be sent
to other BBS's.

@endnode

@node Toss "Toss"

Tossing is the process of reading messages from FidoNet mail packets that
have been received from other BBS's and packing them into new packets and
bundles to send to other BBS's (though the contents of a packet that has
been received from a certain BBS shouldn't be tossed back to the BBS it
came from unless there is a problem somewhere).

@endnode

@node TechMailCfg "TechMail - Configuration"

The TechMail Configuration file (usually BBS:Cfg/TechMail.Cfg) is a normal
ASCII-file and can be created/edited with a normal text editor.

';' and '#' are identifiers for comment lines, if the first non-blank
character of a line is either of these, the parser skips the line.

If a line begins with a '>', the line is executed as an AmigaDOS command
line.

For other lines, the following keywords are valid:

        @{"     4dNames                 " link TM4dNames}
        @{"     Arc                     " link TMArc}
        @{"     BadArea                 " link TMBadArea}
        @{"     Baud                    " link TMBaud}
        @{"     CapabilityConfig        " link TMCapabilityConfig}
        @{"     DefArc                  " link TMDefArc}
        @{"     DeletePackets           " link TMDeletePackets}
        @{"     Dupes                   " link TMDupes}
        @{"     EchoAddress             " link TMEchoAddress}
        @{"     Export                  " link TMExport}
        @{"     FidoNode                " link TMFidoNode}
        @{"     HoldMsgs                " link TMHoldMsgs}
        @{"     IgnoreSeenBy            " link TMIgnoreSeenBy}
        @{"     Import                  " link TMImport}
        @{"     ImportNetMail           " link TMImportNetMail}
        @{"     Inbound                 " link TMInbound}
        @{"     InCharSet               " link TMInCharSet}
        @{"     InPassword              " link TMInPassword}
        @{"     LinkReplies             " link TMLinkReplies}
        @{"     LogFile                 " link TMLogFile}
        @{"     LogWindow               " link TMLogWindow}
        @{"     NetMailArea             " link TMNetMailArea}
        @{"     Outbound                " link TMOutbound}
        @{"     OutCharSet              " link TMOutCharSet}
        @{"     OutPassword             " link TMOutPassword}
        @{"     Route                   " link TMRoute}
        @{"     TaskPri                 " link TMTaskPri}
        @{"     Toss                    " link TMToss}
        @{"     TmpPktDir               " link TMTmpPktDir}
        @{"     UnArc                   " link TMUnArc}
        @{"     UnArcDir                " link TMUnArcDir}

@endnode

@node TMCapabilityConfig "TechMail Configuration - CapabilityConfig"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          CapabilityConfig <filename>

Sets the file to read/write node capabilities from/to.  Only the nodes
listed in the file are kept track of, extended type-2 packets are always
sent to other nodes.  Each line of this file contains:

<address> <mode> <capabilities>

Where <address> is a fidonet address (it can contain wildcards, but this is
not recommended, since the configuration is re-written by TechMail whenever
a different set of capabilities is received from any matching address),
<mode> is "Old" (force FTS-0001 type-2 packets w/o cw), "Auto" (use best
common packet type, in this case always the extended type-2 packet) or
"New" (use the extended type-2 packet format).  The capabilities are
separated by commas and can include the numbers 2-16 and the letter "U".

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No configuration (all nodes are sent FSC-0039 type-2
                extended packets)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        CapabilityConfig BBS:Cfg/CCfg.Dat

@{b}See also:@{ub}       FSC-0039.004

@endnode

@node TMIgnoreSeenBy "TechMail Configuration - IgnoreSeenBy"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          IgnoreSeenBy
                NoIgnoreSeenBy

If IgnoreSeenBy is on, TechMail will ignore the SEEN-BY lines when
exporting echomail.

Warning:  Normally, you shouldn't use this option.  It should only be
necessary if your echo areas have point addresses.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoIgnoreSeenBy

@{b}Example:@{ub}        IgnoreSeenBy

@endnode

@node TMInCharSet "TechMail Configuration - InCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          InCharSet [[zone:]net/]node[.point] <character set>

Sets the input character set to use for nodes matching the address (which
can contain wildcards).  Messages received from one of these nodes are
assumed to be in this character set and converted to ISO (or to whatever
character set is specified as the @{"OutCharSet" link TMOutCharSet} when tossing).  The name of
the character set must include the a full path to the file but not the
.DAT-extension.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No inbound character set conversion

@{b}Example:@{ub}        InCharSet 2:*/*.* BBS:CharSet/SF7

@endnode

@node TMOutCharSet "TechMail Configuration - OutCharSet"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OutCharSet [[zone:]net/]node[.point] <character set>

Sets the output character set to use for nodes matching the address (which
can contain wildcards).  Messages sent to one of these nodes are converted
from ISO (or whatever character set is specified as the @{"InCharSet" link TMInCharSet} when
tossing) to this character set.  The name of the character set must include
the full path to the file but not the .DAT-extension.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No outbound character set conversion

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OutCharSet 2:*/*.* BBS:CharSet/SF7

@endnode

@node TMInPassword "TechMail Configuration - InPassword"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          InPassword [[zone:]net/]node[.point] <password>

Sets the password required to be included in a message packet to import
messages from a node matching the address (which can contain wildcards).
If a message packet contains something other than this password, no
messages are imported and the packet is renamed with the extension
".badpasswd".  Only 8 characters of the password are used.  The password is
not case sensitive.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No password is required

@{b}Example:@{ub}        InPassword 170:10/*.* MyPasswd

@endnode

@node TMOutPassword "TechMail Configuration - OutPassword"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          OutPassword [[zone:]net/]node[.point] <password>

Sets the password that will be put in message packets sent to any node
matching the address (which can contain wildcards).  Only 8 characters of
the password are used.  What the effect of the contents of the password
field of an outbound packet is depends on the remote system.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No password is put in message packets

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OutPassword 170:10/*.* MyPasswd

@endnode

@node TM4dNames "TechMail Configuration - 4dNames"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          4dNames
                OldNames

If 4dNames are used, TechMail will name its outbound files
zone.net.node.point.*, where the last part depends on what the file is for.
If OldNames are used, the outbound files will be named according to the
original echomail specifications.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        4dNames

@{b}Example:@{ub}        OldNames

@endnode

@node TMArc "TechMail Configuration - Arc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Arc [[zone:]net/]node[.point] <archive command>

Sets the archive command to use for a node for archiving mail bundles.
Wildcards are valid for the address.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use default set using @{"DefArc" link TMDefArc}

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Arc 170:10/*.* lha a

@endnode

@node TMBadArea "TechMail Configuration - BadArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BadArea <message area>

Sets the number of the message area to use for bad messages (either
messages that have an echotag that isn't used for any of the existing areas
or dupes if @{"DupesToBad" link TMDupes} is set).

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify a bad message area!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BadArea 9

@endnode

@node TMBaud "TechMail Configuration - Baud"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Baud <number>

Sets the number to set for the baud rate in outbound FidoNet bundles.  (I
don't know what the value is for, but most software ignore it, so you
probably shouldn't worry about this)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Baud 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Baud 2400

@endnode

@node TMDefArc "TechMail Configuration - DefArc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DefArc <command>

Sets the default command to use for archiving bundles.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (use @{"Arc" link TMArc} for every node if you don't specify a default!)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DefArc lha a

@endnode

@node TMDeletePackets "TechMail Configuration - DeletePackets"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DeletePackets
                NoDeletePackets

If NoDeletePackets is specified, inbound mail is renamed (an .old-extension
is added) instead of being deleted after processing.  You shouldn't need to
use this option, but if you do, you should look at your inbound-directory
after each import, since if you have a file by the same name as another
file used to be, the file can't be renamed because the .old-extended
version already exists.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        DeletePackets

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoDeletePackets

@endnode

@node TMDupes "TechMail Configuration - Dupes"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DupesToBad
                KillDupes
                IgnoreDupes

These options determine what to do when a duplicate message is found (a
message with a MSGID-kludge that already exists in the echo area).  If you
have DupesToBad set, the message is impored to the bad-area instead of the
destination echo (which is useful since it allows you to examine any dupes
and find out where they came from).  If KillDupes is set, the message is
not imported.  If IgnoreDupes is set, the system will not even attempt to
detect duplicate messages.  Checking dupes may slow down importing but is
recommended in any large network, especially if you are a hub.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        DupesToBad

@{b}Example:@{ub}        KillDupes

@endnode

@node TMEchoAddress "TechMail Configuration - EchoAddress"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          EchoAddress
                NoEchoAddress

If EchoAddress is set, tossed echo-messages will have the origin set to
your address and the destination to the address the message is being tossed
to.  (Again, I don't know why this should be used, but it seems other
software does this)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoEchoAddress

@{b}Example:@{ub}        EchoAddress

@endnode

@node TMExport "TechMail Configuration - Export"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Export

Turns on @{"exporting" link Export}.  Usually you will probably want to have this on.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Messages are not exported

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Export

@endnode

@node TMFidoNode "TechMail Configuration - FidoNode"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FidoNode [[zone:]net/]node[.point]

Sets your default node-address.  A message areas AKA specification will
override this.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No address, you must specify one.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FidoNode 170:10/101.0

@endnode

@node TMHoldMsgs "TechMail Configuration - HoldMsgs"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          HoldMsgs [[zone:]net/]node[.point]

Tells the system to hold messages for the specified node (ie.  send them
when the system polls you).  Wildcards are valid.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Don't hold messages

@{b}Example:@{ub}        HoldMsgs *:*/*.*

@endnode

@node TMImport "TechMail Configuration - Import"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Import

Turns @{"importing" link Import} on.  Usually you should have this set.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Don't import messages

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Import

@endnode

@node TMImportNetMail "TechMail Configuration - ImportNetMail"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ImportNetMail
                NoImportNetMail

Sets whether the system @{"imports" link Import} netmail with a destination other than your
address.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoImportNetMail

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ImportNetMail

@endnode

@node TMInbound "TechMail Configuration - Inbound"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Inbound <path>

Sets the inbound directory.  This directory is searched for packets and
bundles when @{"importing" link Import} and/or @{"tossing" link Toss}.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Inbound MAIL:Inbound

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Inbound SYS:BBS/MailIn

@endnode

@node TMLinkReplies "TechMail Configuration - LinkReplies"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LinkReplies
                NoLinkReplies

Having LinkReplies set will enable linking replies according to the
REPLY-kludges.  Linking replies may slow down importing.  If you have
@{"dupe checking" link TMDupes} on, this will not make much difference in speed.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        LinkReplies

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoLinkReplies

@endnode

@node TMLogFile "TechMail Configuration - LogFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogFile <filename>

Sets the file to log actions to, describing what TechMail is doing.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No log is kept

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogFile BBS:Logs/TechMail.log

@endnode

@node TMLogWindow "TechMail Configuration - LogWindow"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LogWindow <filename>

Can be used to set a console window for log output.  All log entrys are
written to this window as well as the @{"LogFile" link TMLogFile}, the difference is that the
window isn't appended to or closed until the end of the session.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No log window

@{b}Example:@{ub}        LogWindow CON:20/20/600/80/BBSMail/AUTO/CLOSE/SCREENTechScreen

@endnode

@node TMMaxScan "TechMail Configuration - MaxScan"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MaxScan <messages>

Sets the maximum number of messages to scan when checking for dupes and
reply chains.  (The messages are checked starting with the last message)
Setting this value to zero will cause all the messages to be scanned.  This
will slow importing down quite a lot if there are thousands of messages in
the area.  It is recommended that you set the maximum scan value to a few
hundered messages.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MaxScan 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MaxScan 100

@endnode

@node TMNetMailArea "TechMail Configuration - NetMailArea"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          NetMailArea <message area>

Sets the message area to use for netmail.  All messages that begin with
anything except AREA are assumed to be netmail.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify a netmail area!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NetMailArea 2

@endnode

@node TMOutbound "TechMail Configuration - Outbound"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Outbound <path>

Sets the outbound directory.  This directory is where exported and tossed
mail is put.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Outbound MAIL:Outbound

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Outbound SYS:BBS/MailOut

@endnode

@node TMRoute "TechMail Configuration - Route"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Route [[zone:]net/]node[.point] [[zone:]net/]node[.point]

Tells the system to route all netmail with a destination matching the first
address to be routed to the second address.  Wildcards are valid for the
first address.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Everything is sent to their destination address

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Route *:*/*.* 170:10/100.0

@endnode

@node TMTaskPri "TechMail Configuration - TaskPri"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TaskPri <priority>

Sets the task priority to use for TechMail.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        TaskPri 0

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TaskPri -1

@endnode

@node TMToss "TechMail Configuration - Toss"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Toss

Turns on @{"tossing" link Toss}.  If this is set, @{"Import" link TMImport} must also be specified (but not
the other way around, since if Import is set, but not Toss, the mail can
still be @{"exported" link Export} from your areas), otherwise you will not get the messages
tossed during this session in your message areas.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No tossing is performed

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Toss

@endnode

@node TMTmpPktDir "TechMail Configuration - TmpPktDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TmpPktDir <path>

Sets the directory to create mail packets in.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify a directory!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TmpPktDir T:

@endnode

@node TMUnArc "TechMail Configuration - UnArc"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UnArc <command>

Sets the command to use for unarchiving message bundles.  If you don't know
for sure what your inbound mail is going to be archived with (or you might
have stuff archived using different methods), you should have this set to a
command that can handle several types of archives.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify a command!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UnArc Extract.rexx

@endnode

@node TMUnArcDir "TechMail Configuration - UnArcDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UnArcDir <path>

Sets the directory to extract the packets from a bundle to.  (This is done
by making the directory the current directory when extracting, so your
archiver doesn't need to support a destination directory)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Use the inbound directory

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UnArcDir T:

@endnode

@node TechUserEd "TechUserEd"

@{b}@{i}TechUserEd @{ub}@{ui}is the default user-editor for the TechnoBBS system.  You must
have TechCon running to be able to run TechUserEd.

To run TechUserEd:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechUserEd <users name> [-p<public screen name>]

The gadgets should be self-explanatory, except maybe that Load loads the
user by the name in the Name-gadget.  The password gadget will remain empty
until activated by clicking or using tab from name (security feature).
Starting with TechnoBBS release 0.87 the password is in encrypted form, so
it won't look normal.  Don't try to edit the encrypted form, you can't
figure out a password since it is non-decryptable, you can only change it.
If you change it, you should clear (ctrl-x) the field first.  You will see
the password in normal format until you save the user.

The following keys can be used:

<ESC> Exits TechUserEd

Other keys - look at the gadgets

@endnode

@node TWUserAliasField "TechWWF Configuration - UserAliasField"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserAliasField <misc. id>

Sets the misc. field to search for the alias of the user.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (the alias field in Info.BBS is left empty)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UserAliasField ALIAS

@endnode

@node TWUserAddressField "TechWWF Configuration - UserAddressField"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserAddressField <misc. id>

Sets the misc. field to search for the address of the user.  (This probably
refers to a street address, the specs for WWF aren't very specific about
anything)

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (the address field in Info.BBS is left empty)

#{b}Example:@{ub}        UserAddressField ADDRESS

@endnode

@node TWUserPostalCodeField "TechWWF Configuration - UserPostalCodeField"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserPostalCodeField <misc. id>

Sets the misc. field to search for the postal code of the user.  (Note: The
WWF-Specs said PortalCode but I assume that is a mistake, since a postal
code would be more logical between an "Address" and a "City")

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (the postal(?) code field in Info.BBS is left empty)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UserPostalCodeField POSTCODE

@endnode

@node TWUserCityField "TechWWF Configuration - UserCityField"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserCity <misc. id>

Sets the misc. field to search for the city of the user.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (the city field in Info.BBS is left empty)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UserCity CITY

@endnode

@node TWUserCountryField "TechWWF Configuration - UserCountryField"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserCountry <misc. id>

Sets the misc. field to search for the country of the user.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (the country field in Info.BBS is left empty)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UserCountry COUNTRY

@endnode

@node TWUserPhoneField "TechWWF Configuration - UserPhoneField"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          UserPhoneField <misc. id>

Sets the misc. field to search for the phone number of the user.  The specs
don't say whether this means the data phone or voice phone, but I doubt WWF
uses this (or any of the other user information fields) for anything
important, so use it as you wish.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None (the phone field in Info.BBS is left empty)

@{b}Example:@{ub}        UserPhoneField PHONE

@endnode

@node TWForceISO "TechWWF Configuration - ForceISO"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ForceISO
                NoForceISO

Sets whether the ISO only flag will be set in the Info.BBS file.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        ForceISO

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoForceISO

@endnode

@node TechWWF "TechWWF"

@{b}@{i}TechWWF @{ub}@{ui}is a WWF message-bundler for the TechnoBBS system.

TechWWF is similar to @{"TechQWK" link TechQWK}, the differences are:

Configuration file:

There are no BBSCityStatus, BBSPhone, Goodbye, NewsFile, LimitAreaName or
Welcome configuration entries.  Additional entries are @{"UserAliasField" link TWUserAliasField},
@{"UserAddressField" link TWUserAddressField}, @{"UserPostalCodeField" link TWUserPostalCodeField}, @{"UserCityField" link TWUserCityField}, @{"UserCountryField" link TWUserCountryField},
@{"UserPhoneField" link TWUserPhoneField} and @{"ForceISO" link TWForceISO}.

UserMisc:

QWKASYNC -> WWFASYNC
QWKARC -> WWFARC
QWKUNARC -> WWFUNARC
QWKINCSET -> WWFINCSET
QWKOUTCSET -> WWFOUTCSET

(The character sets are ignored if ForceISO is on)

@endnode

@node TechQWK "TechQWK"

@{b}@{i}TechQWK @{ub}@{ui}is a QWK-bundler for the TechnoBBS system.  You need to have
TechCon running to be able to run TechQWK.

To run TechQWK:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechQWK <node number> <I/O> <configuration>

If 'O' is specified, TechQWK will pack any messages above the user's high
read in message areas that the user has selected into a file in the users
directory called <BBSID>.QWK.  If a file by that name already exists, it
will be deleted before the creation of the new one.  If asynchronous mode
is used, the resulting file will be added to the list of marked files, so
the user can use any download function to download the messages.

If 'I' is specified, TechQWK will look in the users directory for
<BBSID>.REP.  If it can be found, the messages in it will be written to the
BBS's message areas.

The configuration file is a normal ASCII-file and can contain the following
keywords:

        @{"     AutoDelete      " link TQAutoDelete}
        @{"     BBSCityState    " link TQBBSCityState}
        @{"     BBSID           " link TQBBSID}
        @{"     BBSName         " link TQBBSName}
        @{"     BBSPhone        " link TQBBSPhone}
        @{"     BBSSysOp        " link TQBBSSysOp}
        @{"     DoneMessage     " link TQDoneMessage}
        @{"     Goodbye         " link TQGoodbye}
        @{"     LimitAreaName   " link TQLimitAreaName}
        @{"     MaxMsgs         " link TQMaxMsgs}
        @{"     NewsFile        " link TQNewsFile}
        @{"     TmpDir          " link TQTmpDir}
        @{"     Welcome         " link TQWelcome}

The following miscallaneous configuration entries for the user are used by
TechQWK (but are optional to provide):

"QWKASYNC":     Can be set to 0 or 1.  Defaults to 0 if not specified.

"QWKARC":       The command to use for creating an archive to be sent to
the user.  Defaults to "lha a" if not specified.

"QWKUNARC":     The command to use for extracting the files from the
<BBSID>.REP file received from the user.  Defaults to "lha x" if not
specified.

"QWKTASKPRI":   The task priority for TechQWK to set itself at.  Defaults
to 0 if not specified.  Note:  It is recommended that you don't let your
users configure this value themselves!

"QWKINCSET":    The name of the character set (must include the full path,
but not the .DAT-extension of the file) that inbound QWK messages should be
converted from.  (This is the character set the user should use to write
QWK-messages)  If this is not specified, inbound QWK messages will not be
converted.

"QWKOUTCSET":   The name of the character set (must include the full path,
but not the .DAT-extension of the file) that outbound QWK messages will be
converted to.  (This is the character set the user will see the messages as
in their QWK reader if their reader isn't configured to convert it to
something else)  If this is not specified, outbound QWK messages will not
be converted.

You will probably want to run TechQWK from your BBS-script.  To be able to
support the asynchronous operation mode for downloading messages, your
script should check if the users misc.  value 'QWKASYNC' is set to 1.  If
it is, you should run TechQWK (the user can use any download or download
marked files command to download the QWK messages once the process is
finished), otherwise you should call TechQWK synchronously and send the
messages to the user once TechQWK returns.  For uploading messages, you
should receive the file and call TechQWK with or without the 'run' command
depending on the QWKASYNC value.

The TechQWK executable is pure.  You might want to resident it to save some
memory/time in situations in which TechQWK is run several times
simultaneously.

@endnode

@node TQAutoDelete "TechQWK Configuration - AutoDelete"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          AutoDelete
                NoAutoDelete

Tells TechQWK to mark the file as %filename, so that it will be deleted
after it is successfully sent.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        NoAutoDelete

@{b}Example:@{ub}        AutoDelete

@endnode

@node TQMaxMsgs "TechQWK Configuration - MaxMsgs"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MaxMsgs <max. msgs to pack>

Sets the maximum number of messages that TechQWK will pack at a time.  If
you have the temporary directory in ram (you should, since it is much
faster), it is probably a good idea to set this to something reasonable, so
that you won't run out of memory.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        MaxMsgs 500000

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MaxMsgs 1000

@endnode

@node TQBBSCityState "TechQWK Configuration - BBSCityState"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BBSCityState <string>

Sets the string to place in the control.dat-file for the location of your
BBS.  This should be in the form "<city>, <state>" according to the
QWK-specifications.  If the state-part doesn't apply, just put the name of
your country or something there (as in the example).

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify this!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BBSCityState Helsinki, Finland

@endnode

@node TQBBSID "TechQWK Configuration - BBSID"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BBSID <ID>

Sets an 'ID' for your BBS.  This is a string that is used for the first
part of the QWK archive filenames (<BBSID>.QWK and <BBSID>.REP).  The
string is usually the name of your BBS (or an abbreviation) and is limited
to 8 characters (probably since the QWK-format was originally thought up by
someone with a PC).

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify this!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BBSID TECHDEVC

@endnode

@node TQBBSName "TechQWK Configuration - BBSName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BBSName <name>

Sets the name of your BBS as it will be included in the control.dat-file.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify this!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        BBSName TechnoBBS Development Center

@endnode

@node TQBBSPhone "TechQWK Configuration - BBSPhone"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BBSPhone <number>

Sets the phone number of your BBS as it will be included in control.dat.
There is no specified format for this number (I think..), so you can put
anything here.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify this!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        I can't think of one.. (Since my BBS doesn't have a number)

@endnode

@node TQBBSSysOp "TechQWK Configuration - BBSSysOp"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          BBSSysOp <name>

Sets the SysOp name to include in control.dat.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify this!

@endnode

@node TQDoneMessage "TechQWK Configuration - DoneMessage"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DoneMessage <string>

Sets a string to send (along with the normal report) after packing messages
asynchronously.  This should tell the user how to download the packed
messages.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None.  It is a good idea to specify this if you let your
                users use the asynchronous mode!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        The QWK archive has been marked for download

@endnode

@node TQGoodbye "TechQWK Configuration - Goodbye"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Goodbye <filename>

Sets the name of the Goodbye-file in the QWK archive.

Note:  Currently the specified file is not actually added into the archive,
the filename is just written in control.dat.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you might want to specify "GOODBYE", since that's
                what other bundlers seem to do..

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Goodbye GOODBYE

@endnode

@node TQLimitAreaName "TechQWK Configuration - LimitAreaName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          LimitAreaName
                NoLimitAreaName

Sets whether or not the name of a message area will be limited to the 12
characters specified by the QWK-specifications.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        LimitAreaName

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NoLimitAreaName

@endnode

@node TQNewsFile "TechQWK Configuration - NewsFile"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          NewsFile <filename>

Sets the name of the news-file in the QWK archive.

Note:  Currently the specified file is not actually added into the archive,
the filename is just written in control.dat.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you might want to specify "NEWS", since that's what
                other bundlers seem to do.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NewsFile NEWS

@endnode

@node TQTmpDir "TechQWK Configuration - TmpDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TmpDir <path>

Sets the temporary directory to use for creating the QWK message files.  If
you have the memory for it, you will probably want this to be somewhere in
RAM:, since it speeds up the process.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you must specify this!

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TmpDir T:

@endnode

@node TQWelcome "TechQWK Configuration - Welcome"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          Welcome <filename>

Sets the name of the welcome-file in the QWK archive.

Note:  Currently the specified file is not actually added into the archive,
the filename is just written in control.dat.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        None, you might want to specify "WELCOME", since that's
                what other bundlers seem to do.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        Welcome WELCOME

@endnode

@node TechFList "TechFList"

@{b}@{i}TechFList @{ub}@{ui}is a simple filelist-generator.

Starting with version 0.02 (0.91 of the TechnoBBS distribution) TechFList
requires TechCon to be running.

If you don't want the contents of an area to be included in the file list,
add a line containing the string "*NOLIST" (not including the quotes) to
the end of the configuration of the area.

To run TechFList:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechFList <fileroot> <listfile> <header> <comment>

<fileroot> is a path to your root file-directory.  <listfile> is the path
and name of the file the list will be named.  <header> is a file that will
be written in the list file before the actual list.  <comment> is the
comment to set for the list file.

Starting with version 0.02 (0.91 of the TechnoBBS distribution) the
<fileroot> option will be ignored.  (TechFList asks TechCon for the file
data structures, this makes it much faster and enables it to list comments
even if they aren't stored as filenotes)  You should still include
something here so the other options can be correctly identified.

@endnode

@node TechIO "TechIO"

@{b}@{i}TechIO @{ub}@{ui}is a dos-handler that can be used to operate software using std i/o
with TechnoBBS.  It can be used for remote shells, doors etc.  TechIO
requires TechCon to be running.

To start the TechIO-driver:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechIO

After this, you can redirect programs to:

TECHIO:<nodenumber>[/(c|d|e|f|r|s)[/<abort string>]]

The options c, d, e and f specify signals to send to a reader after the
TechnoBBS process aborts io (if the carrier is lost or the node is quit for
any other reason).  The option r causes the io to be switched to raw-mode
(this will also change any other io to the node to raw-mode).  If the s
option is set, the breaks are sent to the input stream of the program in
addition to signalling the task.  The abort string is returned to any read
requests after aborting the io, by default, an eof and 0-length result is
returned, which causes many programs to exit.

You can abort the TechIO process by sending it a ^C break.  This is useful
if you want to close TechCon.

TechIO is not pure.

@endnode

@node TechMenu "TechMenu"

@{b}@{i}TechMenu @{ub}@{ui}is an external script language for the TechnoBBS system.  The
@{"language" link TechMenuLanguage} is similar to C (except much simpler).  TechMenu consists of two
executables:

        @{"     TechMenu        " link TechMenuExe}
        @{"     TechMenuComp    " link TechMenuComp}

The language requires precompilation because this speeds up loading the
menus.

A minor drawback of this menu language is that it eats up lots of memory,
since every node has to load its scripts separately.

@endnode

@node TechMenuExe "The TechMenu executable"

The TechMenu executable is used to load a preprocessed menu script and act
accordingly.  To run TechMenu:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TechMenu <node number> <filename>

Where the filename is that of a preprocessed menu script created by
@{"TechMenuComp" link TechMenuComp}.

TechMenu will fail if TechCon or the given node can't be found.

TechMenu is pure.

TechMenu uses jump tables to load the menu file (ie.  it takes a value from
the file and jumps to the address at that position in an array), which will
probably crash if the file is even slightly corrupt, so make sure that what
you give as an argument is a preprocessed menu script and not something
else.

@endnode

@node TechMenuComp "TechMenuComp"

The TechMenuComp executable is used to preprocess menu scripts.  To run
TechMenuComp:

TechMenuComp <source file> <destination file>

Where the source file is an ASCII file containing data for the menu.  The
destination file created will be tokenized and in the format required by
the @{"TechMenu" link TechMenuExe} executable.

TechMenuComp is pure.

TechMenuComp skips any parts in the source that it can't understand and
displays a warning message for some of these cases.

@endnode

@node TechMenuLanguage "TechMenu - Language"

To write a menu script for TechMenu you must first create an ASCII file,
which is the source for the script, then preprocess it using @{"TechMenuComp" link TechMenuComp}
and finally use it with @{"TechMenu" link TechMenuExe}.

The main elements contained in the ASCII file can be:

        @{"     Command         " link MenuCommand}
        @{"     Execute         " link MenuExecute}
        @{"     MenuName        " link MenuName}
        @{"     MenuText        " link MenuText}
        @{"     Prompt          " link MenuPrompt}
        @{"     HotOn           " link MenuHotOn}
        @{"     LoadMenu        " link MenuLoadMenu}
        @{"     Unknown         " link MenuUnknown}

Comments enclosed between /* and */ can be included between elements.

@endnode

@node MenuCommand "TechMenu - Command"

Command "<id>" [(<options>)] { @{"actions" link MenuActions} }["<name>"];

<id> Specifies what string must be entered at the menu prompt for this
command.

The optional <options> group:

        A:<value> Sets the access level required for using this command.

        G:        Indicates that the command is global, it can be used from
                  any menu.

        M:<value> Sets the mask required for using this command.

        N:<value> Sets the minimum required number of characters to match
                  the command id.  Defaults to 0 (all characters must
                  match).

        O:@{"exp." link MenuExpression}    The expression must be true (not
                  equal to zero) to use this command.

The <actions> are what are executed when the command is entered at the menu
prompt.

The optional <name> string specifies what is sent when the command is
recognized if hotkeys are on.

@endnode

@node MenuExecute "TechMenu - Execute"

Execute { @{"actions" link MenuActions} };

Executes the <actions> when the menu file is loaded.  When you use execute,
everything else in the source file is ignored and you have a script instead
of a menu.

Note: You can't use the arg() function since it has no input to process

@endnode

@node MenuName "TechMenu - MenuName"

MenuName "<string>"

Is used to specify the name of the menu the script file represents.  The
name is currently used for setting the status of the node (the description
of what the user is doing).

@endnode

@node MenuText "TechMenu - MenuText"

A line containing:

MenuText "<filename>"

Is used to specify the file sent using the TechnoBBS @{"SendMenu" link TBSendMenu} command.
This doesn't need to include the extension of the textfile, so that the
users extensions could be used to specify menu type.

@endnode

@node MenuPrompt "TechMenu - Prompt"

Prompt @{"expression" link MenuExpression}

This specifies the prompt text for this menu.

@endnode

@node MenuExpression "TechMenu - Expressions"

A TechMenu expression consists of two alternating types of elements, values
and glues (I can't think of any good words to describe them..) An
expression always begins and ends with a value and can contain one or more
elements.  The value of an expression is the outcome of processing the
values using the glues from left to right.  Internally, it is always a
string, since all the processing is done 'blindly' by calling the evaluate
function pointer in values and glues.

The values can be one of the following types:

@{b}variable:@{ub}  $<id> The value of the variable identified by the id is used.

@{b}string:@{ub}  "<string>" The string can contain ASCII-characters, including LFs
and CRs, which will be part of the string, not ignored as usual.  The
backslash ('\') is used as an escape, to insert a backslash in the string
you must use two backslashes ('\\').  Following the backslash you can have
a '"', which will insert a '"' in the string (since normally this would
indicate the end of the string), a number enclosed in parenthesis (which
will insert the ASCII character represented by the number), an expression
enclosed in parenthesis preceded by the keyword 'parse' (which will parse
the expression at load time only) or an expression enclosed in paranthesis
(which will parse the expression every time it is used).

@{b}inverse:@{ub}  ~<expression> The expression is either terminated by the next
non-alphanumeric character or by closing parenthesis (if the expression was
started with opening parenthesis).  The value of this is the result of a
not operation on the value of the expression.

@{b}logical inverse:@{ub}  !<expression> As an inverse, except that the value is the
logical not of the value of the expresion.

@{b}subexpression:@{ub}  (<expression>) The expression enclosed in parenthesis is
evaluated.  This can be used to affect the order of evaluating the glue
operations.

@{b}function:@{ub}  <name>([<args>]) Inserts the value returned by the function.
The function is either an @{"internal function" link MenuFunctions}, a @{"TechCon function" link TechConARexx} or a
@{"TechnoBBS function" link TechnoBBSARexx} (in which case the first argument, the node number, is
left out).  The arguments are expressions separated by commas.

@{b}immediate value:@{ub} <number> Inserts the number.

The glues can be one of the following (these are the same as in C with the
exception of no precedence):

==      returns boolean true (1) if the values on each side are equal,
false (0) otherwise.  This compares the actual strings.

!=      returns boolean true (1) if the values on each side are inequal,
false (0) otherwise.  This compares the actual strings.

>       returns boolean true (1) if the value on the left side is greater
than the value on the right side, false (0) otherwise.  This compares the
values of the strings.

<       returns boolean true (1) if the value on the left side is smaller
than the value on the right side, false (0) otherwise.  This compares the
values of the strings.

>=      returns boolean true (1) if the value on the left side is greater
than or equal to the value on the right side, false (0) otherwise.  This
compares the values of the strings.

<=      returns boolean true (1) if the value on the left side is smaller
than or equal to the value on the right side, false (0) otherwise.  This
compares the values of the strings.

+, -, * and / perform addition, subtraction, multiplication and division,
to the numeric values of the expressions on each siderespectively.
Remember that there is no precedence, the order of evaluation is always
from left to right for expressions.

++      adds the values of the expressions on each side as strings.

|       performs an or operation between the values on each side.

||      performs a logical or operation between the values on each side.

&       performs an and operation between the values on each side.

&&      performs a logical and operation between the values on each side.

^       performs an exclusive or operation between the values on each side.

@endnode

@node MenuFunctions "TechMenu - Internal functions"

The internal TechMenu functions can be used in expressions only, they will
not function as actions (since their only use is their return value).

arg(@{"expression" link MenuExpression})

returns the argument to the current command indicated by the value of the
expression, where 0 is the actual command and from 1 on are arguments to
that command separated by spaces.

node()

returns the number of the node the script is running on.

str(@{"expression1" link MenuExpression}, @{"expression2" link MenuExpression}, @{"expression3" link MenuExpression})

returns expression3 characters from expression1 starting at expression2,
where 1 is the first character.

len(@{"expression" link MenuExpression})

returns the length of the value of the expression.

upper(@{"expression" link MenuExpression})

returns the value of the expression with all alphabetic characters in upper
case.

lower(@{"expression" link MenuExpression})

returns the value of the expression with all alphabetic characters in lower
case.

split{@{"expression1" link MenuExpression}, @{"expression2" link MenuExpression})

returns the position at which expression2 first appears in expression1.

@endnode

@node MenuActions "TechMenu - Actions"

The following types of actions are possible:

@{b}Assignment:@{ub}

$<id> = @{"expression" link MenuExpression};

Assigns the value of the expression to the variable identified by the id.

@{b}Conditional execution:@{ub}

if(@{"expression" link MenuExpression}) <action>

        or

if(@{"expression" link MenuExpression}) {
    <actions>
}

If the value of the expression is true (anything other than zero) the
action (or actions) is (or are) executed.

If you specify an

else <action>

        or

else {
    <actions>
}

after the 'if' part, the action (or actions) following the 'else' is (or
are) executed if the value of the expression for the 'if' is false (equal
to zero).

@{b}Loop:@{ub}

while(@{"expression" link MenuExpression}) <action>

        or

while(@{"expression" link MenuExpression}) {
    <actions>
}

The action (or actions) is (or are) executed as long as the expression is
true (other than zero).  A check will only be made each time before the
execution of actions is started.

@{b}ARexx command:@{ub}

rexx(@{"expression" link MenuExpression});

The value of the expression will be sent to the current ARexx port as a
command (usually the TechnoBBS node the script is controlling).

@{b}Menu change:@{ub}

menu(@{"expression" link MenuExpression});

The current menu will be changed to the one indicated by the value of the
expression.  The value of the expression must be the filename of the menu
to switch to, not including the path.

@{b}DOS command:@{ub}

dos(@{"expression" link MenuExpression});

The value of the expression is executed as an AmigaDOS command.

@{b}ARexx port change:@{ub}

rxport(@{"expression" link MenuExpression});

Switches the current ARexx port (to send commands to) to the value of the
expression.  If the port is not found, no change is made.

@{b}TechMenu quit:@{ub}

quit;

Exits the TechMenu program.

@{b}Loop or command break:@{ub}

break;

Stops executing either the current while()-loop or the command being
executed (if the break isn't inside a while()-loop).

@{b}Function call:@{ub}

<name>([arguments]);

Calls an external TechnoBBS function or TechCon function and ignores the
value returned.  The arguments are @{"expressions" link MenuExpression} separated by commas.

@endnode

@node MenuHotOn "TechMenu - HotOn"

HotOn "<misc. id>"

Specifies the users misc. value id that indicates hotkeys being on.  If you
use this, you should have all commands available with a minimum length of 1
for recognition.  (Or the entire command consisting of 1 character)

@endnode

@node MenuLoadMenu "TechMenu - LoadMenu"

LoadMenu "<filename>"

Specifies another menu to load.  This must include the full path.  You
shouldn't specify two menus to load each other, since this will result in
an infinite loop.  The specified file must be a preprocessed menufile.  It
will not be loaded during preprocessing, but when the menufile containing
this keyword is loaded.

@endnode

@node MenuUnknown "TechMenu - Unknown"

Unknown @{"expression" link MenuExpression}

Specifies the string to send if an unknown command is entered at the
prompt.  A %s in the string is replaced by the command that wasn't
recognized.

@endnode

@node TrimArea "TrimArea"

@{b}@{i}TrimArea @{ub}@{ui}is a utility for keeping down the size of your message bases.  You
might want to make a script that runs TrimArea for each message area during
some event.  TrimArea requires TechCon to be running.

To use TrimArea:

[run[ <>NIL:]] TrimArea <area number> <max. num. of message files>

Where the area number is the real number (not relative to a SIG) of the
message area and the maximum number of message files is the number of
message files to preserve in this area in addition to the current message
file.

The size of a message file is usually slightly more than 64kB (65536 bytes)
when it's full.  (Actually, it can be any size, depending on the length of
the last message in the file)  You should always keep at least one message
file in addition to the current one (remember, the current file may be
empty or contain only a few messages).

TrimArea is pure.

Example of usage:

Lets say you have 10 message areas and you would like to keep 4 message
files in addition to the current one for each area.  You might create a
file called BBS:Scripts/TrimAreas, which would look something like this:

BBS:Bin/TrimArea 1 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 2 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 3 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 4 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 5 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 6 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 7 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 8 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 9 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log
BBS:Bin/TrimArea 10 4 >>BBS:Logs/Trim.log

You could also have this executed automatically by inserting an entry in
your @{"event configuration" link TCEventFile}:

Hour 2 Command run <>NIL: execute BBS:Scripts/TrimAreas

Using this setup, every morning at 02:00 your message bases would be cut to
a maximum of 4 message files + the current one / area.  A report of deleted
files would be added to a file called Trim.log.

@endnode

@node MkFDat "MkFDat"

@{b}@{i}MkFDat @{ub}@{ui}can be used to automatically create "external" file areas for
devices such as CD-ROMs.  When using MkFDat, TechCon SHOULDN'T be running,
since it could try to update file areas while MkFDat is creating them.


Template:       SOURCE/A,DEST/A,INDEX/K,PATTERN/K,DCOL/K/N,QUERY/S

SOURCE is the root source directory.  This directory itself will only be
scanned for subdirectories, which the file areas will be based on.

DEST is an empty file area directory (it should only contain a
filearea.dat) under which the generated file areas will be.

INDEX (optional) is the name of an index file to use for figuring out
descriptions for files in the created areas.

PATTERN (optional) is a pattern that will be used to match files from
subdirectories of SOURCE.  This is probably most useful as an exclusive
pattern such as "~(#?.info)".

DCOL (optional) is a number indicating the column number (the first column
is column number 0!) in the index-file that the description of a file would
start on.  Defaults to 37.

QUERY (switch) if specified, MkFDat will prompt you for names for the file
areas it creates.  Otherwise the directory names (under DEST) will be used.


                               Using MkFDat:

Create an empty file area.  Make a filearea.dat for it (it shouldn't
contain any extra lines, such as redirections or datafiles!).  This will be
used as a "template" for creating the subareas (the access information will
be the same).  Run MkFDat (see above for options).  The result should be
the following:

The directory structure under SOURCE is duplicated in DEST with subareas
created from the directories.  Each of these subareas (directories) should
contain a filearea.dat (with a redirection to the path in SOURCE and a
*DATAFILE specified as the areas qfiles.dat) and a qfiles.dat (containing a
list of files found in the subdirectory of SOURCE with a description either
taken from the index-file or the comment of the file if the file wasn't
found in the index or there was no index-file specified).  areasort.dat
files are also created.

All of the files created can be edited manually.


                       OR you might not need MkFDat:

If you only need to create a data file for a single directory for a known
area, which MkFDat can't do, you can just use the standard list-command,
e.g.:

list BBS:Files/Area/~(#?.dat) lformat %n/%l/%d/%c dates >BBS:Files/Area/qfiles.dat

You should also have a line containing:

*DATAFILE BBS:Files/Area/qfiles.dat

in BBS:Files/Area/filearea.dat.  This could be used to speed up the
updating of a file area.

@endnode

@node TFreq "TFreq"

@{b}@{i}TFreq @{ub}@{ui}is a FidoNet file request server for the TechnoBBS system.
It can also be used with other software, but it wouldn't provide much
advantage over other equivalent programs.

If TechCon is active when TFreq is run, all of the BBS's file areas that
are available using the access level of the requesting node will be scanned
for the file being requested.  Files can also be requested from specified
directories and by using magic names.

TFreq, like all file request servers, is usually run by a mailer.  The
command line is similar to that of other equivalent programs, so it
shouldn't be difficult to configure the command to use for running TFreq.
The command line is as follows:

TFreq <cfg> <infile> <outfile> <baud> <address>

Where:
        <cfg>           A configuration file (see @{"TFreq Configuration" link TFreqConfig})

        <infile>        The request file (usually #?.REQ), containing a
                        list of files that are being requested

        <outfile>       The file to write a list of the files to send
                        as a result of the request

        <baud>          Baud rate (used for calculating time and access
                        checking)

        <address>       The FidoNet address of the system requesting files

Log information is written to stdout, so you should redirect the output of
TFreq to a logfile (or NIL: if you don't want a log written).

Depending on the configuration, TFreq may send a file containing a report
of the success/failure to find/send the files being requested.  The file is
called tfXXXXXX.txt, where the X's are taken from the system clock (to
provide names that are relatively unique).  This is a plain ASCII file and
will be deleted by the mailer after it is sent.

The @{"TFreq configuration" link TFreqConfig} can be used to configure different access and
limitation levels for different nodes.  The access levels and masks are
like those of users in the TechnoBBS system and control access to file
areas etc..  The limitation levels are used only by TFreq and can be used
to specify different file/byte/time/baud limits for different nodes.

The TFreq executable is pure and can be made resident.

@endnode

@node TFreqConfig "TFreq Configuration"

The TFreq configuration file is a normal ASCII-file and can be
created/edited using a normal text editor.

';' and '#' are identifiers for comment lines, if the first non-blank
character of a line is either of these, the line is ignored.

For other lines, the following keywords are valid:

        @{"     ByteLimit       " link TFByteLimit}
        @{"     DosDir          " link TFDosDir}
        @{"     FileLimit       " link TFFileLimit}
        @{"     MagicName       " link TFMagicName}
        @{"     MinBaud         " link TFMinBaud}
        @{"     NodeAccess      " link TFNodeAccess}
        @{"     SendResult      " link TFSendResult}
        @{"     TimeLimit       " link TFTimeLimit}

@endnode

@node TFMinBaud "TFreq Configuration - MinBaud"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MinBaud <llevel> <baud>

Specifies the minimum connect rate for a limitation level to enable
processing of the file request.  If the system requesting files has a
limitation level of <llevel> and a connection slower than <baud>, the
system will not be allowed to request files.

Note: A minbaud for a limitation level must be configured after the
@{"NodeAccess" link TFNodeAccess}s specifying that level.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No restriction

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MinBaud 1 9600

@endnode

@node TFMagicName "TFreq Configuration - MagicName"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          MagicName <access> <mask> <magic> <real>

<access> is the minimum access level required for a node to be able to
request the file using this magic name.

<mask> is the mask required for a node to be able to request the file using
this magic name.

<magic> is the magic name that can be used in the file request to specify
this file.

<real> is the real name for the file, including a full path.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        MagicName 0 0 FILES bbs:files/textfiles/filelist.lha

@{b}See also:@{ub}       @{"NodeAccess" link TFNodeAccess}

@endnode

@node TFDosDir "TFreq Configuration - DosDir"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          DosDir <access> <mask> <pattern>

Specifies a pattern of files to search through for a file request with a
minimum access of <access> and mask of <mask>.

@{b}Example:@{ub}        DosDir 0 0 HD3:stuff/#?.(lha|lzh|zip|arj)

@{b}See also:@{ub}       @{"NodeAccess" link TFNodeAccess}

@endnode

@node TFNodeAccess "TFreq Configuration - NodeAccess"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          NodeAccess <address> <access> <mask> <llevel>

Specifies the access parameters for a node (or pattern of nodes).  All of
the NodeAccess entries for a limitation level should be specified before
any of: @{"MinBaud" link TFMinBaud}, @{"FileLimit" link TFFileLimit}, @{"ByteLimit" link TFByteLimit}, @{"TimeLimit" link TFTimeLimit} for that level.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        Access, mask and limitation levels of 0 for all nodes

@{b}Example:@{ub}        NodeAccess 2:*/*.* 10 12 1

@endnode

@node TFFileLimit "TFreq Configuration - FileLimit"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          FileLimit <llevel> <files>

Specifies the maximum files allowed to be requested at a time for the given
limitation level.

Note: A filelimit for a limitation level must be configured after the
@{"NodeAccess" link TFNodeAccess}s specifying that level.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No restriction

@{b}Example:@{ub}        FileLimit 0 50

@endnode

@node TFByteLimit "TFreq Configuration - ByteLimit"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          ByteLimit <llevel> <bytes>

Specifies the maximum bytes allowed to be requested at a time for the given
limitation level.

Note: A bytelimit for a limitation level must be configured after the
@{"NodeAccess" link TFNodeAccess}s specifying that level.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No restriction

@{b}Example:@{ub}        ByteLimit 0 5000000

@endnode

@node TFTimeLimit "TFreq Configuration - TimeLimit"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          TimeLimit <llevel> <minutes>

Specifies the maximum minutes that the transfer of the files being
requested should take.  The duration of the transfer is an estimate
calculated according to the connect rate using the very simple and
inaccurate formula: minutes = (bytes / (baud * 7))

Note: A timelimit for a limitation level must be configured after the
@{"NodeAccess" link TFNodeAccess}s specifying that level.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No restriction

@{b}Example:@{ub}        TimeLimit 0 40

@endnode

@node TFSendResult "TFreq Configuration - SendResult"

@{b}Usage:@{ub}          SendResult <header>

Indicates that a result file called tfXXXXXX.txt (where XXXXXX varies) is
sent to the system requesting files containing information on the
processing of the file request.  The contents of the file <header> is
written in the result file before the actual information.  The file
<header> doesn't have to exist.

@{b}Default:@{ub}        No result file sent

@{b}Example:@{ub}        SendResult BBS:Text/FreqHeader.txt

@endnode

@node PDoor "PDoor"

@{b}@{i}PDoor @{ub}@{ui}is a simple Paragon door driver for TechnoBBS.

What it does:

 - Creates a door control port like the one Paragon would normally create
   before running a door

 - Runs the door command, with the node number added after other options

 - Waits for commands from the door

 - Processes the commands sent by the door.  Usually, one of the following
   is done:
     - An ARexx-equivalent of the command is sent to the actual node
     - A stupid default is returned
     - Nothing (unsupported commands)

Currently, rather few commands are supported.  However, the doors that have
been tested seem to work fine.  More commands will probably be implemented
in the future.  The stupid defaults will probably be replaced by
configurable usermiscs.

The command line for using PDoor is:

PDoor <node> <command>

The PDoor executable is pure and can be made resident.

@endnode

@node Suggestions "Suggestions"

If there is a feature that you think this product should have, you can send
a suggestion to @{"Telemedia Software" link Telemedia}.

There's no guarantee that a suggested feature will ever be implemented, but
if the idea is a good and isn't too difficult to implement (some features
would require modification of the entire operation of the whole system), it
will be kept in mind for future releases.

@endnode

@node Bugs "Bugs"

If you find a bug, you can report it to @{"Telemedia Software" link Telemedia}.

In your bug report, you should be very specific in describing the bug.  If
possible, it would be useful if you could provide information on how to
duplicate the bug, since it is hard to fix a bug that occurs under unknown
circumstances.

@endnode

@node Future "Future Enhancements"

It seems that most of the features that are added are from
anywhere except this list.  Here it is, anyhow:

 - Use of hard disk as "virtual memory" for file area storage
 - More options for message-reading
 - Messages to everyone
 - A node chat
 - A line editor (so people without ANSI-terminals can write messages)
 - An easier way to configure the system
 - Areafix support

@endnode

@node Shareware "Shareware"

                                 @{b}Shareware@{ub}

Shareware is a term referring to software that is made freely distributable
so that people can try it out before paying anything for it.  For some
software, the payment is only a contribution to the author, but usually the
payment is considered a "registration" and brings some advantage to the
person registering the software.  For older software, this has typically
been the sending of free updates whenever a new version is released.  This
is stupid, though, since the author can only afford to release a certain
amount of versions, because he (or she?  I've never heard of a female
shareware author, but who knows...) must send the release to everyone who
has registered.  This doesn't work that well anymore, since most good
software (except really small & simple programs (that shouldn't be
shareware anyhow)) keeps getting better with time.  The lifetime of a good
piece of freely distributable (shareware or freeware) software is usually
many years, since the author can always implement new features and improve
old ones (eg. to comply with new standards and utilize new operating system
versions), there is no real limit to the number of overall versions that
can be released.  This is why most modern shareware is distributed as
"crippleware", in which some feature is disabled (or there is some kind of
an inconvenience to the use of the software, such as a requester) in the
freely distributable version.  Registration is required to make the
software fully functional.  Many authors have avoided the problem of either
having to restrict releases or providing only limited free updates by the
use of keyfiles to "unlock" the freely distributable version of the
software.  This provides unlimited free updates for every registered user.
Personally, I think all shareware should work like this.  Someone could
argue that it is too easy to crack the software by disabling the keyfile
checking (or even reverse-engineering the keyfile format), but it's even
easier to copy the registered release of the software, since there is bound
to be someone registering the software who will start spreading it
around...


                      @{b}Positive things about shareware@{ub}

In many ways, shareware is far better than commercial software (especially
on the Amiga).  Here are some common advantages of shareware and freeware
software over commercial software:

 - Utilize the operating system much better (2.x-> features, style guide)

 - Better technical implementation

 - Use less resources

 - Provide advantages for people who know their computer well (at least I
   don't like software that has been made really easy to use, since usually
   it makes the software much less flexible and powerful)

 - Nicer looking (eg. font-sensitive user interfaces are far more common in
   shareware and freeware than in commercial software) and feeling (since
   sw/fw authors more often use their own software themselves)

This seems to indicate that commercial authors care less of the outcome of
the software they are writing (after all, they are writing it because they
have to, not because they want to) or don't know the Amiga that well.


                             @{b}It isn't perfect@{ub}

Modern shareware seems to have some tendencies towards commercialism.  I
don't mean that the software wouldn't be better than commercial software,
but the only thing the authors seem to be concerned about is to get people
to register (for the money!).  This is not the fault of the authors, but
modern society.  Everything in our society and culture shapes the way in
which we think.  In a better world, all software would be free.


                                                 - Ville-Pertti Keinonen

@endnode

@node History "History"

 @{b}0.93@{ub}

 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} *INCSET and *OUTCSET now skip spaces properly...
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Should now work properly even if locale.library is
   unavailable (ie. if you only have WB2.0x and not 2.1 or 3.x)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} File checking commands run asynchronously (Note: For some
   reason, it becomes necessary to include full paths and commands for the
   checking, eg. you might use "SYS:Rexxc/rx BBS:Rexx/CheckFile1.rexx %s"
   instead of just "CheckFile1.rexx %s".  This seems to be a problem with
   AmigaDOS - paths etc. aren't always transferred to new processes)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} ClearUser clears more stuff
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed origin matching for netmail
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Fixed date/protection/filenote when moving files.
 - @{b}TechQWK:@{ub} Date/time processing fixed
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Ctrl-Q operational in non-ANSI chat
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} ':' can be used as the root file directory (in movefile)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Faster logentries (doesn't close the file)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Faster ARexx-command processing
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added autodelete for file transfers ('%' prefix for the
   MarkAnyFile commad or manually added to the users Filemark.dat)
 - @{b}TechQWK & TechWWF:@{ub} Added option for setting autodelete
 - @{b}TechQWK & TechWWF:@{ub} Added max. message/packet limitation
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed another bug in quoting messages
 - @{"TFreq" link TFreq}: Added to distribution
 - @{"PDoor" link PDoor}: Added to distribution
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} No longer crashes if TechQWK/TechWWF imports a message that
   isn't a reply
 - @{b}TechQWK & TechWWF:@{ub} Now changes the mode of the lock on the created
   directory to a shared lock, so that unarchivers that try to get a lock
   on the destination directory should work
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Added @{"DisableLogoff" link TCDisableLogoff} configuration entry
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Checks download access when using numbers to select files
 - TechnoBBS registrations are now handled by @{"Telemedia Software" link Telemedia}

 @{b}0.92@{ub}

 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Added support for FSC-0039 packet format
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Added @{"CapabilityConfig" link TMCapabilityConfig} configuration option
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added -c option to @{"SelectFiles" link TBSelectFiles}
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Removed *DESCFILE (it didn't work)
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Added *DATAFILE (much more useful than *DESCFILE was)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed problem with XPR aborting file transfers w/o any reason
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Improved recognition of quoted lines in a message
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} MessageCheck doesn't abort on first unavailable message
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"ReWriteMsg" link TBReWriteMsg} command
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} xpr_setserial returns correct dte rate
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"MoveFile" link TBMoveFile} command
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"DelFile" link TBDelFile} command
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Uses custom semi-pooled memory allocations for file areas
   (This speeds up reading the area data and reduces memory usage)
 - @{"MkFDat" link MkFDat} created
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Changed the operation of redirection (modified by a datafile
   specification)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} xpr_fopen(), xpr_fclose(), xpr_fread(), xpr_fwrite() and
   xpr_fseek() now use a custom file handle structure including the
   filename.  This eliminates the need for a NameFromFH() call in
   xpr_fclose, which caused problems with transfers through parnet from a
   KS1.3 machine
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} When using a @{"TempSendDir" link TBTempSendDir}, files are copied using direct
   inline routines instead of calling the dos "copy" command through
   SystemTagList().  This should improve the speed of using a TempSendDir
 - @{b}TechWWF and TechQWK:@{ub} Now informs if there are no areas selected when run
   in the background
 - Some changes to Answer, see Util/Answer.doc
 - Programming changes, see Programmer/TechPrg.guide
 - Lots of bugfixes I forgot to add to this list (and can't remember)

 @{b}0.91a@{ub} - TechCon only bugfix release

 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Fixed a bug that trashed some low memory if a file area had any
   free or forbidden files configured

 @{b}0.91@{ub}

 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Sets redraw flag after time left warning
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Aborting timer.device I/O during a file transfer could hang
 - @{b}TechMail, TechnoBBS and TechCon:@{ub} Fixed address parsing
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Sends correct XPR init string for bi-directional transfers
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Improved XPR routines
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} When creating a packet, decides on the origin address based on
   the zone of the destination address (searches throught the AKAs for a
   matching zone number).  If no match is found, the primary address (the
   one configured in your TechMail.Cfg and other configurations) is used
 - @{b}TechMenu & TechMenuComp:@{ub} Access and mask limitation work now (requires
   recompilation)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} The origin address for netmail is chosen according to the
   zone of the destination.  If no match is found, the AKA of the netmail
   area (or if there is no AKA, your primary address) is used
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} When reading messages, again jumps to the next message if the
   current one is unavailable (instead of trying to load the current
   message forever)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} ARexx commands only skip one space between a command and its
   arguments
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} SendASCII doesn't put EOLs after over-sized lines anymore
 - @{b}TechUserEd:@{ub} The never-fully-functional and not-too-useful gadgets have
   been removed and replaced by better ones
 - @{b}TechUserEd:@{ub} Better font sensitivity, now uses screen font
 - @{b}TechUserEd:@{ub} More keyboard shortcuts
 - @{b}TechUserEd:@{ub} The listviews are now larger (it should make editing easier)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Displays free space on device for uploads
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} String list now includes the Y/N prompt strings.  You can now
   have other characters accepted in addition to Y and N by editing the
   strings  (Note: Y and N will continue to be accepted)
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Fixed echo tag matching
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Added @{"IgnoreSeenBy" link TMIgnoreSeenBy} option
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Fixed inbound character set matching
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Checks *INCSET and *OUTCSET for echo areas.  The specified
   character set will be used for conversions instead of the nodes default
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Added *DESCFILE for file areas
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"TempSendDir" link TBTempSendDir} option
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} File data structure locking added
 - @{b}TechFList:@{ub} Complete rewrite, source included with distribution, now
   requires TechCon to be running
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"ConvertMsg" link TBConvertMsg} command
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Areas in the message editor area selection are now sorted by
   SIGs, if there are SIGs configured
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} No longer converts ;30; in a color sequence to ;30;37; for
   the console
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"ListFiles" link TBListFiles}: Added G option
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"SelectFiles" link TBSelectFiles}: Shows first line of long description instead of
   short comment if available
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Text files shown when logging on etc. don't really contain
   anything anymore (it's easier to see that you have to edit them)

 @{b}0.90@{ub}

 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"ListFiles" link TBListFiles}: SO option sorts backwards compared to SN
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} ARexx scripts shouldn't lock up when exiting, I'm not sure if
   this bug fix helped, there may still be problems
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"XPR 2.001" link bixfer} support added for bi-directional file transfers
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"DlAndReceive" link TBDlAndReceive} command added
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Fixed problem with references in filext.dat to unknown files
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed transfer window look when using a proportional font
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Combined message editor & chat routines
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Modifications to message editor and chat : Backspace now
   drags the text on the line when wrapping to the end of the previous line
   if possible.  Del drags the text on the next line to the current line if
   it fits.  Cursor movement sideways now wraps.
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"BiDirOpts" link TBBiDirOpts} configuration option
 - @{b}TechQWK & TechWWF:@{ub} Safer carrier locking (it is now performed earlier
   and on node 0, too)
 - @{b}Install script:@{ub} Now works with paths containing spaces
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Netmail area now uses the hiwater mark (speeds up operation)
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Packets and bundles are now sorted by their datestamps before
   importing
 - @{b}Documentation:@{ub} Some mistakes corrected
 - @{"TrimArea" link TrimArea} created
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Support for TrimArea
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} No attempts to load messages lower than LowMsg (more speed)
 - Added information for programmers to the distribution.

+, as always:
 - Some small changes & bug fixes that I forgot to add to this list

 @{b}0.89@{ub}

 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added -t and -s options to @{"WriteMsg" link TBWriteMsg}
 - @{b}TechQWK and TechWWF:@{ub} Compiler options corrected for smaller size (no
   symbol names included in the executables)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS and TechCon:@{ub} The uploader and long description of files are
   now stored in 'filext.dat'
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added -l option to @{"ListFiles" link TBListFiles}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"StoreUploader" link TBStoreUploader} and @{"MaxDescLines" link TBMaxDescLines} configuration options
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Now uses screen font for intuitexts
 - @{b}TechIO and TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added ACTION_WAIT_CHAR support
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Doesn't get confused if a user has previously existed when
   saving/loading
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Chat and message editor now allow cursor down to move below
   the existing area.  Empty lines below the cursor are removed to avoid
   unnecessary "bouncing"
 - @{b}TechnoBBS and TechCon:@{ub} Added file numbering.  The numbers are always
   from newest to oldest
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added -m option to @{"ListFiles" link TBListFiles}
 - @{b}TechCon and TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added Sig.Dat to the @{"message base configuration" link MessageConfig}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} New ARexx commands @{"SelectSIG" link TBSelectSIG} and @{"SelectSIGArea" link TBSelectSIGArea}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} New ARexx functions @{"CurrentSIG" link TBCurrentSIG}, @{"SIGName" link TBSIGName} and @{"SIGtoReal" link TBSIGtoReal}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"FastCon" link TBFastCon} configuration option
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"ChgDesc" link TBChgDesc} and @{"SetUploader" link TBSetUploader} commands
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"SaveExt" link TBSaveExt} command
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added possibility for the @{"FileCheck" link TBFileCheck} to set a description and
   uploader for a file.
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed @{"SetUserProtocol" link TBSetUserProtocol} and @{"SetUserLanguage" link TBSetUserLanguage}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"MarkFile" link TBMarkFile}, @{"Download" link TBDownload} and @{"GetFilePath" link TBGetFilePath} now accept numbers
 - @{b}Scripts:@{ub} Some problems fixed.  The example scripts in the distribution
   are now similar to the ones I actually use (no more alternate ones for
   those, since keeping the other ones updated with all the new features
   would be a waste of time, since nobody likes them anyhow)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Oops... I forgot to make space for the new strings in 0.88

 @{b}0.88@{ub}

 - @{b}TechMenuComp:@{ub} Removed an unnecessary warning message, since it only
   indicates the end of an expression
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Improved transfer success checking
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Improved upload/download look
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Remove in the download prompt now accepts wildcards
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed several small bugs in the upload/download routines
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Uploads now also affect the average cps rate
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added quiet option to @{"MarkFile" link TBMarkFile}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Files not downloaded successfully are placed back in the
   marked file list
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Prevents a user from uploading a 'User.Dat' (renames as
   'User_Dat') and 'FileMark.Dat'
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Marked messages are saved to a users MsgWait.Dat
   when logging off.  You must use MessageCheck to load them
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Marked files are saved to a users FileMark.Dat when logging
   off.  You must use the new routine @{"LoadFileMark" link TBLoadFileMark} to load them
 - @{b}TechnoBBS and TechCon:@{ub} After an upload, the uploaded files are added to
   the global filelist, the entire list is not updated
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Upload/download now bring up a file requester on the local
   node
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Opening/closing the nodes window will now work during file
   transfers
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Accepts window/TechCon messages while waiting in xpr_sread
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed bug when saving empty message
 - @{b}TechIO:@{ub} Fixed bug when aborting a programs I/O
 - @{b}TechIO:@{ub} New 's' option for sending the breaks to the input stream
 - @{b}TechIO and TechnoBBS:@{ub} ^C and ^D signals are sent in cooked mode
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Now uses the rastport font for calculating the height of the
   window, not the default font
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} The node window can no longer be closed during a chat
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Entering a chat from the nodes window while being paged will
   now close the chat request window
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"SelectFiles" link TBSelectFiles}
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Always sets SERF_RAD_BOOGIE and SERF_XDISABLED when opening
   the serial.device
 - @{b}Answer:@{ub} See Answer.doc
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added double buffered asynchronous serial output to the
   XPR-routines, controlled by @{"DefXPRBuffer" link TBDefXPRBuffer} and @{"MaxXPRBuffer" link TBMaxXPRBuffer}
 - @{b}BBSLogOn.rexx:@{ub} SetAccessPreset "User/NewUser.acc" fixed to
   SetAccessPreset "User/Preset/NewUser.acc"
 - @{b}Main Menu:@{ub} There won't be a "hole" in the user listing anymore (caused
   by the Preset-directory)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS and TechCon:@{ub} Fixed several bugs with deleting files (such as
   killing a user using TechUserEd)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Changing the file area is slightly more user friendly (it
   exits after any input except changing the area to the parent)
 - @{b}Other:@{ub} Included an alternate set of menus and scripts
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Fixed reply linking (parsing of the REPLY: kludge)
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Faster linked list handling
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} A users time left is now updated during transfers
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} The free time menu item is now updated properly
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Time left warnings are no longer displayed during a chat
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"FreeChatTime" link TBFreeChatTime} option
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added @{"HasMsgAcc" link TBHasMsgAcc} function
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added newline before re-displaying the file list prompt after
   mark/download
 - @{b}TechnoBBS and TechWWF:@{ub} Limits the lengths of the date fields in messages
   written to prevent lockups when using strange locales

 @{b}0.87@{ub}

 - @{b}TechCon and TechnoBBS:@{ub} Passwords are now stored in a non-decryptable
   encrypted form.  This prevents anyone who could look at someones
   User.Dat from finding out their password.  Even the SysOp is unable to
   know what the passwords used are (though the SysOp can change the
   passwords).  Old (stored) passwords will be encrypted when a user is
   loaded, so you won't have to delete your users because of this change.
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} @{"CheckPassword" link TBCheckPassword} added, @{"GetPassword" link TBGetPassword} shouldn't be used
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed bug with pasting text from the clipboard to the message
   editor.  (Some garbage followed the text if there were linefeeds)
 - @{b}TechMenu:@{ub} Now uses less memory and loads faster
 - @{b}TechCon and TechnoBBS:@{ub} Now use faster routines for linked lists
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Loading messages shouldn't cause an address error on a 68000
   anymore
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Er.. I had forgot to update the text in the about-requester
   when TechnoBBS was first released..  I hope nobody thought they had an
   illegal copy!
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Menus improved slightly
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} When replying to a private message in a non-private area the
   reply is now private by default
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed bug when replying to some messages
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Previous in reading messages now functions properly even if
   the previous message is unreadable.  (Scans messages backwards to the
   previous readable message)
 - @{b}TechMenuComp:@{ub} Warning messages are now displayed for some errors in the
   mene source
 - @{b}Install script:@{ub} Fixed a slight bug, there was `cd' where there should
   have been `cd`.
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Unjoins areas not available to a user when loading so that the
   user doesn't have access to areas joined previously
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Starting a chat will now always activate the window and move
   the screen to the front
 - @{b}TechWWF:@{ub} Sets the write/reply access bit used bit according to the new
   WWF-specifications
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} ClearUser now also clears the users highreads and areamodes
 - @{b}TechCon and TechnoBBS:@{ub} Pressing the chat button on the page request now
   leaves the window/screen open if it must be opened
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} The 2-column output when listing file areas higher than 10 on
   the same row now has the right number of spaces
 - @{b}TechUserEd:@{ub} Fixed(?) the height of the listview-gadgets
 - @{b}TechUserEd:@{ub} More keyboard shortcuts, access presets used
 - @{b}Other:@{ub} Access presets now in BBS:User/Preset
 - @{b}TechMenu and TechMenuComp:@{ub} Added @{"Execute" link MenuExecute}

 @{b}0.86@{ub}

 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Improved asynchronous signal handling to prevent locking up
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} XPR transfer window now only shows the name of the file, not
   the full path
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Any character above or equal to 128 accepted as '[' for inbound
   ANSI-sequences
 - @{b}TechMail:@{ub} Character set conversions and password support
 - @{b}TechQWK:@{ub} Character set conversions
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Added color to more of the internal routines
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} 2-column file- and message-area listings in selection
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Added @{"ScreenFont" link TCScreenFont} and @{"ScreenFontSize" link TCScreenFontSize} options
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Fixed bug with sorting areas (areas were only sorted when the
   files were originally listed, not when they were read from files.dat)
 - @{b}TechFList:@{ub} Now hides everything ending with .dat, not only files.dat and
   filearea.dat
 - @{b}TechCon:@{ub} Fixed bug when reading event configurations with comments
 - @{"TechWWF" link TechWWF} created
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed outer bevelbox in the transfer window to non-recessed
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Improved recursive SendBBSMsg() call handling (still
   dangerous, though)
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed bug when writing messages to a reply chain with dead
   messages in it
 - @{b}TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed bug with loading character sets
 - @{b}TechWWF and TechQWK:@{ub} Fixed bug when the user had no selected areas (the
   temporary directory created wasn't deleted)
 - @{b}TechCon and TechnoBBS:@{ub} Fixed problem (not actually a bug) with pattern
   matching of names

 @{b}0.85@{ub} - First public beta release

@endnode
